<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 30 Rioters Taken to Tanzanian Court </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Thirty people who have
participated in a riot were taken to court in Tanzanian capital
Dar es Salaam Monday charged with unlawful assembly and procession
and malicious damage to property.
</P>
<P>
The accused include an Imam of the Manyema Mosque, Juma Mbukuzi
Salum, and 29 Moslem followers. They were arraigned before the
Kisutu Resident Magistrate's Court.
</P>
<P>
The demonstration in which the people were taking part last
Friday developed into a riot in areas close to the mosque.
</P>
<P>
Rioters threw stones, bottles and iron pieces at the police
while policemen fired tear gas and used pistols, dogs and horses
to disperse the mob.
</P>
<P>
The police held 96 rioters, but have released most of them in
the past two days as their role in the demonstration was minimal.
</P>
<P>
At the court, the accused denied the charges and were remanded
in custody until August 16.
</P>
<P>
Prosecution led by Assistant Commissioner of Police, Leonard
Mashaka, objected to bailing the accused on the grounds that the
situation at the scene of the event is still tense and that they
should remain in custody for social security according to the
Criminal Procedure Act of 1985.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Tanzanian Minister of Education and Culture Juma
Kapuya tabled a move before the National Assembly, seeking the
right for Moslem girls to wear hijab, or Moslem head scarf, in
common schools and attend Friday prayers.
</P>
<P>
Kapuya, a Moslem himself, later withdrew the move amid concerns
of the majority of members of parliament, who claimed that
Tanzania is a secular country in which students in common schools
are supposed to wear school uniforms when attending classes.
</P>
<P>
Kapuya's change of position has caused wide protests from
Moslems and they organized a demonstration that resulted in the
riot Friday.
</P>
<P>
Tanzanian Vice-President Omar Ali Juma, has urged people to
maintain peace and security in the country and guard against those
who use religious forums to fulfil their ill intentions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
