<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-02 19:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Palestinians Work to Seek Reconciliation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Ahead of the final status talks
with Israel on thorny issues, the Palestinians were exerting
efforts to seek ways of healing rifts and reaching national
reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat led a delegation of
his Fatah movement to a meeting in Cairo with that of the radical
Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine (PFLP), headed by
Abu Ali Moustafa, PFLP's deputy leader.
</P>
<P>
This was the first meeting between the two most powerful groups
in the Palestine Liberation Organizaton (PLO) since it signed the
Oslo accord with Israel in 1993. Fatah is the major faction to
support the Palestinian-Israeli peace talks while the PFLP is
opposed to the peace agreements signed between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of the two sides were upbeat after seven hours
of meeting, which they described as a success. Salim al-Zanoun, a
senior Fatah leader and speaker of the Palestine National Council,
said the successful talks will encourage other Palestinian
factions to join the dialog aimed at reaching national
reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
Ahmed Qureia, also known as Abu Ala, a member of the Fatah
Central Committee and speaker of the Palestinian Legislative
Council, said the national reconciliation dialog is important for
the Palestinian people approaching the final status talks with
Israel.
</P>
<P>
Moustafa said the two sides "are on the right path." In spite
of the differences over the Palestinian-Israeli talks between his
group and Fatah, they would work together to reinvigorate PLO's
role, he said.
</P>
<P>
He reaffirmed opposition to the Oslo accord but said the PFLP
would be "in front of the political reality and look to the
future."
</P>
<P>
The two groups have agreed to hold talks again in a number of
weeks and decided to form a committee comprising of two members
from each side to put forward proposals for reactivating PLO's
role and realizing national reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the Fatah-PFLP meeting, Arafat chaired in Cairo on
Saturday a meeting of the Central Committee of Fatah, which
included three top members who are opposed to the Oslo accord.
</P>
<P>
The three are Director of the PLO Political Department Farouk
Qaddoumi, Fatah military leader Mohammed Jihad and Mohammed
Ghoneim, in charge of the movement's organization. Arafat called
the meeting to facilitate their attendance in a bid to bridge
the gap inside the movement.
</P>
<P>
It is essential to work out a unified stance at this critical
phase before the final status talks with Israel, Faisal Husseini,
Palestinian minister for the Jerusalem affairs said after the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
The Fatah Central Committee insisted that all the signed
agreements be implemented before the negotiations for a final
peace deal, Husseini said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
