<HEADLINE> Most of Zambia's Privatized Assets Bought by </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 2 (Xinhua) -- The majority of participants in
the Zambian privatization program are locals who have purchased
small- and medium-size state-owned assets covering the entire
spectrum of the economy.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest issue of Privatization News available
here Monday, out of more than 249 companies and units privatized
by the Zambia Privatization Agency, 65 percent have been bought by
Zambian citizens while the remaining 35 percent have gone to
foreign investors who bought mostly larger companies.
</P>
<P>
And of the few outsiders who have participated in the program,
50 percent of them were minority share-holders who had rights of
preemption over government share-holding and this was outside the
control of the privatization agency, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The majority of employees in privatized companies will always
be locals because they work happily in their countries, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
Local participation in the economy should not only be seen in
the context of Zambians buying companies offered by the
privatization agency and shares floated through its efforts, but
also in the ability of locals setting up their own companies and
purchasing shares from any other private firm listed on the stock
market, it said.
</P>
<P>
At the moment, all efforts must be put in initiatives that will
help Zambians to reconstruct the country's economy, said the
report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
