<HEADLINE> NATO to Replace Its Troops in Albania by September </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, August 2 (Xinhua) -- The North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) will send new troops by September to replace
its forces currently stationed in Albania called the AFOR, or the
majority of them, an AFOR press officer here said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Most of the AFOR are expected to leave Albania on September 1
as their "humanitarian mission" is closing, said Lt. Col. Helge
Eriksen.
</P>
<P>
The details of the mission of new NATO forces and its commander
have not been clearly decided by the North Atlantic Council so
far, but the council has decided that NATO will remain in Albania,
he said.
</P>
<P>
The NATO officer from Norway disclosed that the new NATO forces
are likely to be called AFOR II, and the number of the forces
could be around 2,000.
</P>
<P>
Part of the new NATO forces' mission is likely to provide
logistic support to NATO forces in Kosovo (KFOR) and engage in
some infrastructure construction work in Albania, Eriksen said.
</P>
<P>
The new forces will include troops from all the NATO members
and part of the AFOR, and the commander might come from Italy, he
added.
</P>
<P>
According to the Albanian Telegraphic Agency, the North
Atlantic Council decided at the Sarajevo summit Friday that NATO
troops will continue to stay in Albania.
</P>
<P>
The AFOR's mission in Albania may trace back to mid-April when
a group of 270 French troops arrived in the Albanian port of
Durres on April 12 during the Kosovo crisis. The number of troops
once reached over 7,000 in Albania. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
