<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2000GMT, Monday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT -- A high-ranking Lebanese delegation Monday left here
for Damascus to make preparatory coordination with Syria for the
anticipated resumption of peace talks with Israel.
</P>
<P>
The delegation is made up of Lebanese Foreign Ministry Director
General Zafer al Hassan and Yahya Mahmassani, diplomatic advisor
of Prime Minister Salim Hoss.
</P>
<P>
The delegation will discuss with senior Syrian officials the
possible topics in talks with Israel. (BC-Lebanon-Syria-Peace)
</P>
<P>
GAZA -- Chairman of Palestinian National Authority Yasser
Arafat on Monday accused the Israeli government of trying to evade
the implementation of the Wye River agreement.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian leader made the accusation while speaking to
reporters in front of his presidential premises here upon return
from Egypt where he held talks Sunday with an opposition
Palestinian faction on Palestinian unification.
</P>
<P>
Arafat said the failure of Sunday's Palestinian-Israeli
negotiations over the implementation of Wye agreement demonstrated
Israel's attempt to avoid enforcement of the terms of the
agreement. (BC-Arafat-Israel-Wye)
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy said on Monday
he was astonished that Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat had
accused Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak of trying to get out of
some of Israel's peace commitments.
</P>
<P>
During his meeting with Barak last week, Arafat had agreed to
consider Israel's proposal over implementation of the Wye accord
and pledged to give an answer after two weeks, Israel Radio quoted
Levy as saying.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israeli Environment Minister Dalia Itzik paid a
visit to Gaza on Monday and met Palestinian officials.
(BC-Israel-Palestinians)
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- A major Palestinian opposition faction has turned down
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat's offer to join the Palestinian
National Authority (PNA).
</P>
<P>
Before leaving for Damascus, Syria, Maher Taher, spokesman for
the Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine (PFLP), told
reporters here on Monday that Arafat has proposed that PFLP
officials take posts in the PNA.
</P>
<P>
"But we will not take part" in the Gaza-based administration,
Taher said, adding that the PFLP will not "deal with the Oslo
agreement and its consequences," referring to the 1993 peace deal
with Israel. (BC-Egypt-Palestinians-Faction)
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Two Palestinian groups on Monday underlined the need
for joint efforts to reach a national reconciliation for
recovering the legitimate rights of the Palestinian people.
</P>
<P>
The Fatah movement, led by Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat,
and the radical Damascus-based Popular Front for the Liberation of
Palestine (PFLP) held talks on Sunday in Cairo on ways of healing
rifts and mending fences.
</P>
<P>
A joint communique was issued on Monday on the talks.
</P>
<P>
In the communique, the two groups emphasized the necessity to
hold dialog among all Palestinian forces to augment national
reconciliation and unity. (BC-Egypt-Palestinians-Communique)
</P>
</TEXT>
