<HEADLINE> Annan Concerns Over Numerous Deaths in Colombia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 2 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan Monday voiced his concern for the loss of lives in the
conflict of Colombia, and urged the parties concerned to pursue
dialogue and negotiation for peace, a U.N. statement said.
</P>
<P>
"The Secretary-General wishes to express his concern for the
loss of lives caused by the conflict in Colombia," said the
statement, issued by a U.N. spokesman here. "The past weeks have
brought a worrisome escalation of violence, at a time when peace
negotiations were set to take place."
</P>
<P>
"Since Friday, bomb attacks have led to numerous deaths, and
with them the international community and the United Nations had
harbored hope and expectation at the prospect that negotiations
might finally ensue," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"The Secretary-General urges parties to the conflict to pursue
dialogue and negotiation and wishes to encourage the respect of
international humanitarian law as well as the protection of the
civilian population," the statement added.
</P>
<P>
Rebels have bombarded a small mountain town in northwest
Colombia with home-made missiles, killing up to 15 people and
destroying at least 40 buildings, said reports Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
