<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian Woman Beaten to Death for Exorcism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 2 (Xinhua) -- An Egyptian man who claimed to be a
soul healer beat a sick woman to death in a bid to exorcise her
demons, police said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Fatin Mohammed el-Seyed, 40, died Sunday in a village outside
Cairo after she was thrashed by Hamid Mahmoud Mohammed with a
thick bamboo stick, a police officer said.
</P>
<P>
Police have arrested both Mohammed and el-Seyed's husband, a
hotel worker, who took el-Seyed to the so-called healer, the
officer was quoted by the country's Middle East News Agency as
saying.
</P>
<P>
El-Seyed, the mother of a 12-year-old boy, had been suffering
from an unknown ailment, the policeman said. Mohammed told the
husband that el-Seyed was haunted by evil spirits which needed to
be exorcised.
</P>
<P>
Police said Mohammed beat her for 15 minutes and said she would
be fine after four "demons" had left her body. But when the
husband tried to talk to el-Seyed, he found she had become
motionless.
</P>
<P>
A coroner found she had died of a heart attack.
</P>
<P>
Beating as a form of exorcism is common in Egypt among peasants
and low-income people who often believe that certain ailments stem
from the devil having penetrated the body. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
