<HEADLINE> NATO Likely to Nominate New Chief Wednesday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 2 (Xinhua) -- The North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) is likely to nominate its new chief Wednesday
during the weekly ambassadorial council meeting, NATO sources said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
British Defense Minister George Robertson is now the
front-running candidate as NATO ambassadors held informal talks
Monday to sort out any opposition to his nomination.
</P>
<P>
Britain proposed Robertson as its official nominee for the post
as the NATO chief last Friday.
</P>
<P>
The 53-year-old British defense minister played an active role
in the 11-week air campaign launched by the Western military
alliance against the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Javier Solana of Spain is now holding the post of NATO chief.
</P>
<P>
Solana succeeded Belgian Willy Claes after the latter resigned
in 1995 following a domestic scandal of bribery.
</P>
<P>
Solana is to take up the post of foreign policy and defense
coordinator of the European Union.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Monday, some sources close to the Western military
alliance said that the nomination council meeting could be held as
early as Tuesday if all ambassadors agreed and were backed up by
their respective governments on Robertson's nomination. 
</P>
</TEXT>
