<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinian Factions Pledge to Work for National </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Two Palestinian groups on Monday
underlined the need for joint efforts to reach a national
reconciliation for recovering the legitimate rights of the
Palestinian people.
</P>
<P>
The Fatah movement, led by Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat,
and the radical Damascus-based Popular Front for the Liberation of
Palestine (PFLP) held talks on Sunday in Cairo on ways of healing
rifts and mending fences. A joint communique was issued on Monday
on the talks.
</P>
<P>
In the communique, the two groups emphasized the necessity to
hold dialog among all Palestinian forces to augment national
reconciliation and unity.
</P>
<P>
Fatah is the major faction to support the Palestinian-Israeli
peace talks while PFLP and several other factions are opposed to
the peace agreements signed between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
The two groups called for means to put an end to the Israeli
occupation of the Palestinian land and eliminate the Jewish
settlements on the occupied Palestinian territories.
</P>
<P>
Fatah and PFLP reiterated their commitment to the basis of the
Palestinian national principle, foremost of which is the refugees'
right to return to their homeland and the establishment of an
independent Palestinian state with Jerusalem as its capital.
</P>
<P>
The two sides underlined the importance of reactivating the
role of the Palestine Liberation Organization, the sole legitimate
representative of the Palestinian people.
</P>
<P>
The two groups have agreed to continue dialog and form a
committee to follow up what has been agreed on in the talks and
work out executive mechanisms, according to the communique.
</P>
<P>
Fatah and PFLP have decided to set up a committee comprising of
two members from each side to make a list of proposals for
reinvigorating PLO's role and reaching national reconciliation.
</P>
</TEXT>
