<HEADLINE> Stepashin Insists on Aid to All Victims in Balkan War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Russian Prime Minister Sergei
Stepashin said Monday that international organizations should
extend support to everyone whose life was affected by the NATO
military action in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
"Exempting any country from this process would obstruct the
talks," Stepashin said at a meeting with Montenegrin President
Milo Djukanovic, the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"Human rights must be protected, but there are other methods
besides bombings," Stepashin said, referring to NATO's 78-day air
campaign against Yugoslavia that destroyed much of the Balkan
country's infrastructure, besides military installations.
</P>
<P>
The international community has acknowledged that the
consistent stand of Russia and President Boris Yeltsin contributed
to the halting of the bloodshed in the Balkans, Stepashin said.
</P>
<P>
Djukanovic, before his departure late Monday, said he was
"firmly convinced that Moscow understands our position and
supports our efforts for building a democratic and economically
open society."
</P>
<P>
"The issue of possible secession from the Federal Republic of
Yugoslavia was not discussed" during the visit, Djukanovic said.
</P>
<P>
"Montenegro is not pursuing this goal," he said. However, the
republic "would have to consider its future" within the Federation
if "Serbia ignores our call for the deepening of democratic and
market processes in the Yugoslav Federation," Interfax quoted
Djukanovic as saying.
</P>
<P>
On the situation in Kosovo, Djukanovic said the international
peacekeepers there are unable to protect non-Albanians from
Albanian terrorists. "The Balkans settlement will become much more
difficult if ethnic cleansing is tolerated" (in Kosovo), he said.
</P>
<P>
Djukanovic was here as a guest of Russian Foreign Minister Igor
Ivanov. He also met with Moscow Mayor Yuri Luzhkov Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
