<DOCNO> XIE19990803.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Not to Quit Southern African Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe will not pull out of the
Southern African Development Community (SADC), a Zimbabwean
diplomat said in Nairobi Monday.
</P>
<P>
Shame Tarumbiswa, counsellor of the commerce section at the
Zimbabwean High Commission in Kenya, told Xinhua that he saw no
reason of withdrawing from the regional community.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe has duly paid its membership fee to the regional
organization, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Nairobi-based East African weekly Monday predicted that the
SADC could soon be watching Zimbabwe abandon it for the Common
Market for East and Southern Africa (COMESA).
</P>
<P>
The report attributed a possible withdrawal of Zimbabwe from
the SADC to the massive trade imbalance in favor of South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Tarumbiswa said that Zimbabwe's deficit in its trade with South
Africa is significant, particularly in textiles.
</P>
<P>
However, Zimbabwe would not pull out of the SADC because of the
 dominance of South African economy in the region, he noted,
joking that "where can we go, to the lion's mouth?"
</P>
<P>
He noted that Zimbabwe, also a member of the COMESA, looks at
the SADC as "a stepping stone" toward the COMESA.
</P>
<P>
Integration is a process, he said, citing that the three
countries of the East African Cooperation, Kenya, Tanzania and
Uganda, are moving toward a East African Community. All of the
three countries are COMESA members.
</P>
<P>
The SADC and the COMESA are harmonizing in their policies and
programs so as to achieve an African Economic Community sooner,
said Tarumbiswa.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the report that Tanzania was considering quitting
the COMESA and remaining a SADC member, the commerce official said
he doubted that Tanzania would really do that as integration is
the common aspiration of the African countries.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania participated actively in the COMESA meetings in
Nairobi in mid- May this year, Tarumbiswa said.
</P>
<P>
The report said that "the two groups are intended to become
customs unions and it is a technical impossibility for one state
to belong to two different customs unions because goods imported
without duty from one union can then be exported without duty to
the other."
</P>
<P>
Tarumbiswa pointed out that there would be safeguards
addressing he issue. That's why the rules of origin has been
discussed in the integration process.
</P>
<P>
The SADC is aiming to achieve a free trade area on January 1,
2000 while the COMESA has been counting down on achieving a free
trade area by October 31, 2000.
</P>
<P>
Ten members of the 14-member SADC, including Zimbabwe, Tanzania
and Namibia, are also members of the 21-member COMESA.
</P>
<P>
Quitting the COMESA is not unprecedented. Mozambique and
Lesotho left in 1997.
</P>
<P>
But it is believed that Mozambique is to return to the COMESA,
possibly at the next COMESA summit in Mauritius.
</P>
<P>
Mozambique had allegedly pulled out of the COMESA because its
parliament did not agree to pay membership fees to both the SADC
and the COMESA. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990803.0025 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
