<HEADLINE> Annan Shocked by Indian Railway Tragedy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 2 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan "was shocked" Monday to learn the tragic train crash in
India, which may have killed as many as 250 people and injured
more than 1,000 others, a U.N. spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Fred Eckhard, the U.N. spokesman, issued a statement here,
saying that "the Secretary-General was shocked to hear of this
morning's railway accident in India."
</P>
<P>
Annan "deeply regrets the heavy loss of life, and shares the
grief of the many afflicted families," the spokesman said in the
statement.
</P>
<P>
Two express trains collided head-on at a station in eastern
India early Monday, crumpling into fiery, twisted wreckage and may
have killed as many as 250 people and injured more than 1,000
others. 
