<HEADLINE> USAID Provides $300M to Angola in Past 4 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, August 2 (Xinhua) -- U.S. International Development
Agency (USAID) has provided Angola with more than 300 million U.S.
dollars in humanitarian aid over the past four years, an official
of the organization said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
William Garvelink, an official with the Department of
Assistance for Catastrophy of the USAID, said he kept consulting
government officials, institutions of the United Nations and
non-government organizations on the establishment of a mechanism
for offering humanitarian aid to the people living in the areas
controlled by UNITA rebels.
</P>
<P>
The humanitarian situation in Angola has seriously deteriorated
after a full-scale war renewed between the government troops and
the National Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA)
rebels led by Jonas Savimbi.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. official noted that the USAID officials will meet with
the Angolan authorities before making a platform designed to help
the displaced people in the war-torn southern African country.
