<HEADLINE> S. African Shares End Weaker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 2 (Xinhua) -- South African shares ended
weaker Monday, but off their worst levels despite the underlying
weaker trend in financial markets.
</P>
<P>
Gains in the resources, gold and chemicals sectors aided the
benchmark all-share index to come off its lows.
</P>
<P>
At the 16:00 local time (14:00 GMT) close on the Johannesburg
Stock Exchange, the all-share had lost 0.46 percent, the
industrials fell 0.53 percent, financials skidded 1.27 percent,
while the all-gold index gained 0. 82 percent and resources were
0.65 percent higher to finish at a new closing high of 4,794.20.
The chemicals index rose 0.77 percent as Sasol, Polifin and AECI
dominated the sector.
</P>
<P>
"The all-share index has been down for most off the day. The
recovery in the gold price turned the gold index around to join
the positive looking resources index. The market was not exciting
at all and most of the active shares were acquisition driven,"
said Michael Yates, director at ING Barings.
</P>
<P>
Anglo American, the world's largest gold conglomerate, also
edged higher amid news that it is to buy a 23 percent stake in
Australia's Anaconda Nickel.
</P>
<P>
Anglo American topped the most value traded shares to close
322.00 rand (53.6 U.S. dollars), rising 3.60 from its previous
close.
</P>
<P>
The Information Technology index was 1.37 percent softer with
Dimension Data falling 1.45 percent or 35 cents from Friday's
close of 24.10 rand (four dollars).
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones has recovered and that would be an advantage for
equities to stage a recovery, market sources said.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones Industrial Average had gained 0.91 percent or
97.5 points from Friday's close of 10,655.2 by 16:40 local time
(14:40 GMT).
</P>
<P>
The bond market followed the weaker rand to touch a weakest
level of 14. 755 percent after closing at 14.520 percent Friday.
</P>
<P>
The rand also weakened and was last quoted at 6.1900 rand per
dollar from a previous close of 6.1550 rand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
