<HEADLINE> Russia to Test Early Warning System in Belarus Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 2 (Xinhua) -- A top Russian defense official
said Monday that an early warning facility in Branovichi of
western Belarus will be tested before the end of the year and
"supplied to the armed forces in 2000."
</P>
<P>
The early warning facility is expected to restore the single
radar field over the western and northwestern sectors after the
elimination of the radar facilities in Skrunde, Latvia, said
Colonel-General Vladimir Yakovlev, commander of the Russian
Strategic Rocket Forces, during a trip to Baranovichi.
</P>
<P>
"The radar facilities at Skrunde will be completely
decommissioned this year," the Interfax quoted Yakovlev as saying.
</P>
<P>
The commander said that the "hole" opened up in the single
radar field is being filled by the facilities located at Sofrino
and Chekhov outside Moscow.
</P>
<P>
However, Yakovlev said, "the loss of a single information field
will inevitably affect the stability of our nuclear weapons
complex."
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the first (space-based) and second
(ground-based) echelons of the early-warning system "are essential
to decision-making, including as regards the use of nuclear
weapons."
</P>
<P>
He said that in accordance with interstate agreements, Russia
will supply information on rocket attacks to those countries of
the Commonwealth of Independent States that have Russian early
warning systems. The countries include Belarus, Ukraine,
Kazakhstan and Azerbaijan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
