<HEADLINE> Writethru: 15 Injured in Opposition Strike in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 2 (Xinhua) -- At least 15 people, including one
policeman and three train passengers, were injured during the
first day of the opposition-sponsored 30-hour nationwide strike in
Bangladesh Monday.
</P>
<P>
A police constable was seriously injured in the capital city
when a teargas shell bounced back from his own gun, and three
train passengers were injured when pickets hurled hand-made bomb
on them in a railway station in Dhaka.
</P>
<P>
Some 16 persons were detained by police so far for "creating
anarchy" and "damaging public property." Some 5,000 riot police
and paramilitary Bangladesh Rifle forces were deployed at
important points in the capital.
</P>
<P>
Barring some stray incidents, the shutdown was largely peaceful
and life was almost normal throughout the country. Most of the
government, semi-government and private offices remained open, and
rickshaws and buses plied the streets defying the strike.
</P>
<P>
Shops and business establishments adjacent to the main roads
were mostly closed and long distance buses and trucks remained off
the roads in the capital.
</P>
<P>
The situation in Chittagong, Rajshahi, Khulna, Barisal and
Sylhet, headquarters of another five divisions of the country,
also remained mostly normal. The country's largest seaport, the
Chittagong seaport, did not deliver or accept any cargo during the
day but loading and unloading inside the port continued as usual.
</P>
<P>
The opposition alliance, including the Bangladesh Nationalist
Party, the Jatiya Party, the Jamaat-e-Islami and the Islami Oikya
Jote, started the strike, the eighth of its kind sponsored by the
opposition alliance this year, to protest the government's
decision last week allowing "corridor to India in the name of
transshipment."
</P>
<P>
The ruling Bangladesh Awami League, meanwhile, brought out
anti-strike processions in the capital protesting the 30-hour
strike enforced by the opposition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
