<HEADLINE> S. African Money Rates Steady Ahead of Reserve </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Money market rates in South
Africa were steady Monday ahead of Tuesday's release of the
Reserve Bank's gross foreign reserves.
</P>
<P>
The repo rate (the central bank's prime lending rate) eased two
basis points to 13.630 percent Monday from 13.650 percent last
Friday, as the Reserve Bank matched the estimated liquidity
requirement of 12.2 billion rand (six billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Market sources said this week's local focus would be on gold
and foreign reserves data due Tuesday at 8:00 a.m. local time.
</P>
<P>
The market expects better foreign and gold reserves data due to
 the listing of Old Mutual on the London Stock Exchange on July
12, which brought in some five billion rand (83 million dollars)
into South Africa.
</P>
<P>
The consensus forecast for the Reserve Bank's gross foreign
reserves is a 1.5 billion rand (250 million dollars) increase to
36.6 billion rand (6.1 billion dollars), while the net open
forward position is expected to drop by one billion dollars to
17.3 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The money market is on hold until after (former labor minister
Tito) Mboweni has taken over as Reserve Bank governor, and for a
couple of weeks after that.
</P>
<P>
Mboweni will be inaugurated on August 7. The first trading day
after his inauguration is August 10, as August 9 is a public
holiday.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, Mboweni hosted a dinner for journalists and told
them that exchange rate targeting was a discredited policy.
</P>
<P>
"Even the Bank of England in September 1992 saw that exchange
rate targeting was not a viable central bank policy," Mboweni
said.
</P>
<P>
"That leaves two policy options, a currency board system, where
you link your monetary policy to another country such as the U.S.,
or inflation targeting, which most central banks are following
currently. I will give the Reserve Bank's choice on August 24,"
Mboweni said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
