<HEADLINE> Tanzania's Trade Deficit Rises to $101Million in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania's trade deficit in
June 1999 has widened to 101 million U.S. dollars from 86.1
million in the previous month, the central bank said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The deterioration was caused by a significant decrease in
exports by 21. 4 percent, coupled with 7.4 percent increase in
imports, the Bank of Tanzania said in an economic report.
</P>
<P>
Total export earnings during June declined by 21.4 percent to
23.1 million dollars, from 29.4 million dollars in May after both
traditional and non-traditional exports decreased, the bank said
in its June issue monthly economic review.
</P>
<P>
Earnings from traditional exports decreased by 23.4 percent to
8.2 million dollars in June, from 10.7 million dollars in the
previous month due to declines in both export volumes and unit
export prices, the report said.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, decreases in export volumes of coffee,
cotton, tea, tobacco and cashew nuts registered 11.9 percent, 76.1
percent, 1.8 percent, 68.7 percent and 100 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
During June, non-traditional exports, including minerals,
manufactured goods, sisal products, fish and fish products and
horticulture products, declined by 20.3 percent to 14.9 million
dollars, from 18.7 million dollars in the previous month.
</P>
<P>
Total imports during June increased by 7.4 percent to 124.1
million dollars, from 115.5 million dollars recorded in May.
</P>
<P>
The import bills for two major categories, namely, capital
goods and intermediate goods, registered increases of 5.9 percent
and 80.8 percent respectively, the report said.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, it noted, imports for consumer goods
recorded a decrease of 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
The increase in the imports of capital goods is mainly due to
the increase in the importation of transport equipment, building
and construction goods associated with the ongoing investments in
the mining sector and new investments in the construction sector.
</P>
</TEXT>
