<HEADLINE> Canadian Ministers Welcome WTO Ruling against Brazil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Canada welcomed Monday the latest
World Trade Organization (WTO) ruling against a Brazilian export
program for its aerospace industry.
</P>
<P>
Canadian International Trade Minister Sergio Marchi and
Industry Minister John Manly said that the WTO Appellate Body had
confirmed its earlier decisions on Brazil's PROEX export subsidy
program.
</P>
<P>
"We are pleased with the decision on PROEX, since it addresses
a serious threat to the Canadian aerospace industry and resolves a
long-standing dispute between Canada and Brazil," the ministers
announced.
</P>
<P>
The WTO Appellate Body confirmed that Brazil must withdraw the
PROEX export subsidies within 90 days, rejecting Brazil's appeal
against an earlier WTO ruling that PROEX was a prohibited export
subsidy program.
</P>
<P>
But Canadian officials did not say if the country would comply
with another ruling by the same WTO Appellate Body that Technology
Partnerships Canada was inconsistent with WTO rules in its support
for regional aircraft.
</P>
<P>
Minister Manley said he would move quickly to consult with
industry stakeholders on opinions for implementing this decision.
</P>
<P>
Canada and Brazil took their disputes over export subsidies to
the WTO in July 1998. In its April ruling this year, WTO panels
decided that Brazil's PROEX program and Technology Partnerships
Canada were prohibited export subsidies. The two countries later
appealed respectively again to the WTO in objection to the related
rulings.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian Aerospace sector comprises more than 400 companies
and employs approximately 60,000 people across Canada. Sales of
the Canadian products in this sector exceeded 15 billion Canadian
dollars (about 995.85 million U.S. dollars) in 1998, according to
the official information. 
</P>
</TEXT>
