<HEADLINE> U.S. Conducts Another Antimissile Missile Test </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 2 (Xinhua) -- The United States conducted
another antimissile missile test in White Sands Missile Range in
New Mexico State Monday morning, military officials said.
</P>
<P>
The antimissile missile hit a simulated warhead, the second
success for a controversial 3.8 billion defense system that failed
in its first six attempts, according to the officials.
</P>
<P>
The Theater High-Altitude Area Defense (THAAD) system is
designed to use ground-launched missiles to destroy high-altitude
enemy missiles from 1,280 kilometers away or more, a distance that
current U.S. weapons cannot reach.
</P>
<P>
The system has been criticized as too expensive and unreliable.
The weapon's prime contractor, Lockheed Martin Corporation, was
fined 15 million U.S. dollars after its sixth test failed in May.
THAAD scored its first hit on June 10 in New Mexico State.
</P>
<P>
The Defense Department has since said that it will cancel the fine
if the defense contractor improves THAAD performance and that it is
confident Lockheed Martin can successfully develop the system.
</P>
</TEXT>
