<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Small Arms Create Big Casualties in World </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Small in size and light in
weight, small arms and light weapons have created big casualties
across the globe.
</P>
<P>
More than tanks, missiles and mortars, one half billion small
arms and light weapons are circulating in the world today.
</P>
<P>
They are responsible for killing three million people in the
last decade alone. No fewer than 8 of every 10 people killed were
children and women.
</P>
<P>
The availability of such arms can undermine ceasefire, peace
agreement and conflict resolution, make it easier for
ex-combatants to resort to banditry, crime and insurrection, and
hinder socio-economic development.
</P>
<P>
As part of their advocacy campaign against the uncontrolled
spread of small arms, the United Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF)
and the U.N. Department for Disarmament Affairs have produced an
exhibit entitled "Taking Aim at Small Arms Defending Child
Rights."
</P>
<P>
The small arms show, which is under way at the U.N.
headquarters, is comprised of informative text panels,
photographs, posters, 3-D cut-outs, children's drawings, icons,
interactives and video presentations which document the scourge of
small arms and light weapons, indicate their worldwide prevalence
and reveal the toll they take on human lives -- especially
children.
</P>
<P>
Some of the issues explored in the exhibit are child soldiers,
the arms trade, demobilization, disarmament and post-conflict
peace-building.
</P>
<P>
Jayantha Dhanapala, U.N. undersecretary-general for disarmament
affairs, has said, "The United Nations is determined to combat the
small arms plague, which affects the daily lives of millions of
people and consumes not only a great part of the international
community's resources, but also at risk its most important
investment in the future -- its children."
</P>
<P>
The exhibit also highlights the positive actions undertaken
internationally to promote further actions by both governments and
the general public in elimination of the trade in small arms.
</P>
<P>
"The spread of small arms creates serious global problem and
require an equally urgent response because the lives and futures
of millions of children are at stake," UNICEF Executive Director
Carol Bellamy said. "These weapons have probably extinguished more
young lives than they have protected."
</P>
<P>
Since 1990, small arms have become the weapons of choice in 46
of the 49 conflicts around the world. Two million firearms are
circulating in Central America, seven million in West Africa and
10 million in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
"During the past decade, some 300,000 children participated in
over 30 conflicts worldwide. Such participants would have been
impossible without access to small arms, which children can easily
strip and reassemble," Bellamy said, adding that the international
spread of inexpensive small arms has made it easier to turn young
children into soldiers.
</P>
<P>
In the United States, children also fall victims to the small
arms abuse. On a typical day in the United States, nearly 13
children lose their lives to handgun killer. Gunfire killed 4,643
children in 1996.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, close to 300 companies in 52 countries were
manufacturing small arms and light weapons. The European Union and
the United States together account for 80 percent of the four
billion U.S. dollars a year in global arms trade.
</P>
<P>
To curb the illicit availability and illegal trade is the
concerted aim of the world community.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations, the 185-nation organization which has prime
responsibility for world peace and security, plays a dominant role
in actions against the spread of small arms and light weapons in
part of its sweeping efforts to resolve conflicts and promote
development all over the world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990803.0043 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
