<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Notes Limited Recovery in Russia But Warns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 2 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary Fund
(IMF) said on Monday that a "limited recovery" has emerged in Russia,
but warned that "considerable risks remain."
</P>
<P>
In its annual review of the Russian economy, the IMF said there has
been a turn-around in 1999, noting that industrial output during
April-June exceeded the levels of one year earlier by over 5 percent
on average.
</P>
<P>
"Foreign exchange market pressures have also eased and the ruble
has stabilized, while monthly inflation has come down to under 2
percent in June, reflecting a tightening of fiscal and monetary
policies," the IMF said.
</P>
<P>
Russia's overall balance of payments position has also become
stronger as the external current account has swung from a deficit of
2.7 billion U.S. dollars in the first quarter of 1998 to a surplus of
4.8 billion dollars in the first quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
The Russian government's macroeconomic framework for 1999 envisages
that the economic contraction will bottom out in 1999, with output for
the year as a whole declining by 2 percent. The external position
should strengthen, enabling a small increase in foreign reserves.
</P>
<P>
But the IMF warned that "the limited recovery and the measure of
stability achieved in recent months would prove unsustainable unless
strenuous and determined efforts were made to reduce the fiscal
deficit and to accelerate structural reforms."
</P>
<P>
The IMF said Russia's failure to tackle underlying fiscal problems
had been the main factor behind last year's financial crisis, when the
government devalued the ruble and defaulted on some domestic debts.
</P>
<P>
The IMF stressed that Russia's extremely difficult economic and
financial situation, amid a sharp cut-back in access to external
financing, should lend a new sense of urgency to the need for
fundamental and lasting reform.
</P>
<P>
"Directors stressed that fiscal consolidation remains at the heart
of the adjustment effort," it added.
</P>
<P>
The IMF approved last week a 17-month stand-by credit of 4.5
billion dollars for Russia to support the government's 1999-2000
economic program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990803.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Says Difficult to Carry out Wye Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 2 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. State Department on
Monday acknowledged that carrying out the Wye agreement would be
difficult.
</P>
<P>
"There has been no change in that commitment, as far as we
know," State Department spokesman James Rubin said. "But even with
the best of intentions, it's going to take time to work out these
differences. We expect this to be difficult."
</P>
<P>
Israel would relinquish 13.1 percent of the West Bank to the
Palestinians under the Wye accord, reached last October between
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and former Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu with U.S. President Bill Clinton as the broker.
</P>
<P>
But Netanyahu called a halt for the implementation of the Wye
accord after ceding 2 percent of the land.
</P>
<P>
Ehud Barak after assuming the premiership of Israel in July,
advocated to combine the Wye agreement with the final status
negotiations, which means a delay of carrying out the accord as
was stipulated.
</P>
<P>
Because of opposition from the Palestinian Authority, Barak
again proposed on Sunday that October 1 would be the target date
for carrying out the remaining part of the accord.
</P>
<P>
But the Palestinians again rejected the proposal on Monday,
saying a two-month delay in withdrawal raised concerns that the
prime minister was trying to wiggle out of Israel's commitments to
pursue peace.
</P>
<P>
A senior Palestinian official has said that working-level talks
with Israel had broken down without agreement.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration, however, indicated on Monday that
private contacts were continuing productively between Israel and the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
"There is real contact -- effective contact, greater contact and
discussions -- between the two parties themselves, without the need
for the United States to involve itself in every single way," Rubin
said.
</P>
<P>
He said the discussions "tend to be a little more constructive
than the characterization some might put on them."
</P>
<P>
"Even with the best of intentions, it's not surprising that the
differences that developed over three years will not be worked out
overnight," Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
"Clearly, both sides will need to work together if we're going to
determine ways and means to carry out and implement the Wye River
agreement," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
