<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Grants $37 Million for Nairobi Blast Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 2 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. government has allocated
37 million U.S. dollars to assist the victims of August 7, 1998
bomb blast in Kenyan capital Nairobi and to rebuild the affected
buildings and businesses, a U.S. official said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Country Director Jonathan Conly of the U.S. Agency for
International Development (USAID) said in Nairobi that the
Cooperative Bank House will be the main beneficiary of the grant
and its reconstruction is estimated to cost 10 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Conly said that the bids for reconstruction tender of the house
are ready in September this year and the contract will be offered
by the end of October, adding that the reconstruction work on the
building is expected to be completed by September 2001.
</P>
<P>
The 37-million-dollar grant for blast victims was approved last
 September by the U.S. Congress.
</P>
<P>
Those children who lost their parents in the blast will be
extended 2.5 million dollars for a three-year primary and
secondary school fees assistance.
</P>
<P>
The education program will be implemented through the Kenya Red
Cross which has so far identified 898 children for school fees
assistance, Conly said.
</P>
<P>
The official said that nine million dollars will go to
reconstructive surgery and other medical care for the blast
survivors and 3.7 million for 60 buildings affected by the
bombing.
</P>
<P>
The USAID also contracted KPMG Peat Marwick to verify losses to
small- and medium-sized businesses, and cheques will be issued
within next two weeks, Conly added.
</P>
<P>
More than 200 people died and some 5,000 injured in last
year's Nairobi bomb blast. 
</P>
</TEXT>
