<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT, August 3 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL -- Some 50 people were feared dead or missing while South
Korea was hit by torrential rains, floods and landslides caused by
Typhoon Olga, local media reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Olga is heading for the heart of the peninsula and the death
toll could rise as communications with isolated areas are restored,
disaster officials said.
</P>
<P>
An intense low-pressure system which had affected upper South
Korea moved slowly southward, after dumping up to 20 centimeters (
8 inches) of rains in the central part South Korea, weather
officials said.
</P>
<P>
Gale-force winds and rains drenched South Korea's southern and
western coasts.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of houses were reportedly flooded in Cheju, an island
100 kilometers off the peninsula's south coast. High sea waves
were seen pounding the shores of the island and gale-force winds
uprooted trees and telephone poles.
</P>
<P>
Five domestic airports and all domestic ports were closed while
the Korea Meteorological Administration Office issued a nationwide
typhoon alert early on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Olga would pass near the capital Seoul by evening and head
directly for the Democratic People's Republic of Korea, weather
officials said. (SKorea-Typhoon)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Six people were killed and nine others injured in an
armed attack by the outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK) in
southeastern Turkey late Monday night.
</P>
<P>
A group of PKK rebels attacked a mini-bus at Cigdemli village
in Silvan town of Diyarbakir province, killing six people and
wounding nine others, the semi-official Anatolia News Agency
reported Tuesday. (Turkey-PKK)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LAGOS -- At least 50 people were killed in recent ethnic
clashes in Nigeria's southwest Ondo state.
</P>
<P>
The death toll, caused by a renewed fighting erupted last week
between the Ilaje and Ijaw communities in Ondo Sate, was confirmed
by the delegates from both ethnic groups meeting at the state
governor's office Monday, the Daily Times newspaper reported
Tuesday. (Nigeria-Ethnic Clash)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- The Indian government Tuesday decided to set up a
Commission for Railway Safety in the wake of the Gaisal train
tragedy, Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the commission will investigate the cause of this
accident and the series of accidents in the past. (India-Railway
Safety Commission) 
</P>
