<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain: Pinochet Can Go Home If Spain Withdraws Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The British government confirmed
Tuesday that if Spain dropped its request for extradition, former
Chilean leader Augusto Pinochet, who has been detained in London
for the past 10 months, would be free to go home.
</P>
<P>
"If there are no charges and the case is withdrawn, then there
is no reason to hold him. If Spain decides to withdraw the
extradition, then court proceedings will cease," a spokeswoman for
the Home Office (interior ministry) said.
</P>
<P>
She noted that Pinochet was not facing charges in Britain.
</P>
<P>
Her remarks were made after Spain said at the weekend it was
considering a request by Chile that the case be settled by
arbitration.
</P>
<P>
Pinochet, 83, was arrested in a London hospital last October at
Spain's request to face charges of murder, torture and hostage
taking.
</P>
<P>
A Spanish judge accused Pinochet of being responsible for the
disappearances and deaths of 3,000 people and wanted him to be
extradited from Britain to face trial in Spain.
</P>
<P>
Pinochet had claimed sovereign immunity to prosecution for
crimes committed between 1973 and 1990 when he was in power.
</P>
<P>
The retired general, under house arrest at a mansion southwest
of London, is due in court next month for an extradition hearing.
</P>
<P>
The Home Office spokeswoman said Pinochet was not facing
charges in Britain. She also expressed doubt that Britain would
have to prosecute Pinochet if Spain dropped its case.
</P>
<P>
"I don't know if the UK would be obliged," she said.
</P>
<P>
Chile, which wants Pinochet to be sent home, asked the Spanish
government last week to accept arbitration to decide whether
Pinochet should be tried in Spain -- hoping to engineer an
alternative which would spare Pinochet trial in Madrid. 
</P>
</TEXT>
