<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Twenty Anthrax Cases Registered in Kyrgyzstan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Twenty anthrax cases have been
registered in southern Kyrgyzstan, the Interfax news agency
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The epidemic is spreading from the Osh region and over 250
other people were believed to have contacted with the beef that
contains the bacterium that causes anthrax, Interfax said, quoting
a source with the central Asian country's Health Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Anthrax is an infectious, usually fatal disease of warm-
blooded animals, especially cattle and sheep. It can be
transmitted to human beings through contact with contaminated
animal substances, such as hair, feces or hides, and is
characterized by ulcerative skin lesions.
</P>
<P>
Kyrgyzstan's Extraordinary Anti-Epidemic Commission has
imposed a state of emergency in the southern areas of the country.
Regional and local authorities and veterinary services have been
told to tighten their control over the slaughter of animals and
the sales of meat, Interfax said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990803.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 14:18 </DATE_TIME>
