<HEADLINE> Iran Demands Turkish Response on Inquiry of Air </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Iran on Tuesday demanded an
immediate response from Turkey on its inquiry into air raids of
Iranian border outpost and villages two weeks ago, in which five
Iranians were killed and another 10 injured.
</P>
<P>
According to the official Islamic Republic News Agency (IRNA),
the demand was made by Iran's ambassador to Turkey Mohammad
Hussein Lavasani, who on Monday held talks with Turkish Foreign
Ministry director general for the Middle East affairs.
</P>
<P>
IRNA said the two discussed the upcoming meeting of the
neighbors' joint security commission to be held in Ankara on
August 9-13.
</P>
<P>
Iran has claimed that four Turkish warplanes on July 18
intruded into its territorial space in the Piranshahr area in the
northwest and dropped bombs, causing human and material damages.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has hinted that Iran was replacing Syria in hosting
Turkey's Kurdish rebels, who have been leading a separatist war in
southeastern Turkey for more than a decade. Ankara succeeded last
year in forcing Damascus to drop its support for Kurdish
guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
IRNA said the Turkish official told the Iranian ambassador
that Turkey will "announce the result of the inquiry made by a
fact-finding delegation which visited Iran to review the border
incidents."
</P>
<P>
Turkish military and civilian officials visited the border
region in northwestern Iran on Wednesday to investigate the air
raids. They were expected to compile their findings in a report.
</P>
<P>
Lavasani stressed the need for an immediate completion of the
inquiry into the air raids and demanded Turkey's serious
attention to Iran's sensitivities and concerns regarding the
issue.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal Kharazi has met with his
Turkish counterpart Ismail Cem on the sidelines of the Balkan's
Stability Pact Summit in Sarajavo to mend fences. Their talks were
described as "constructive" and Turkey has expressed the hope
that two of its soldiers arrested in Iran will be released soon.
</P>
<P>
There seemed to have been more downs than ups in
Iranian-Turkish relations, but the two sides stressed the need
for "common understanding" to strengthen bilateral relations in
all fields. 
</P>
</TEXT>
