<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Camp for Congo Refugees to Be Set Up in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 3 (Xinhua) -- A new Red Cross refugee camp will
be built in western Tanzania to relieve operation pressures as
people continue to flee the fighting in the Democratic Republic of
Congo.
</P>
<P>
The Nairobi Regional Delegation of the International Federation
of Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies said here Tuesday the
existing Red Cross camp at Lugufu, 90 kilometers east of the Lake
Tanganyika port of Kigoma, has been stretched beyond capacity for
weeks.
</P>
<P>
The International Federation Tuesday launched a 1.7
million-Swiss-franc (around 1.1 million U.S. dollars) appeal to
shelter up to 30,000 refugees in a buffer camp close to Lugufu,
said the Nairobi Regional Delegation in a media release.
</P>
<P>
The strategy will allow the Red Cross to limit the population
of its old camps to 60,000, which is still 20,000 more than it
was designed for, the release said.
</P>
<P>
According to the Federation, in Lugufu, food rations have
already been reduced and the water supply will have to be
decreased shortly. Meanwhile sickness and mortality rate are on
the rise due to colder weather.
</P>
<P>
Georg Nothelle, head of the International Federation in
Tanzania, said that the new camp will operate as an extension of
Lugufu, which is run by the Tanzania Red Cross with support from
the International Federation.
</P>
<P>
Nothelle said the Federation faces a serious shortfall of funds
for its existing operation, adding that the refugee influx has
effectively doubled the resources needed over the second half of
the year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
