<HEADLINE> Pyongyang Defends Satellite Launch as Sovereign Right </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PYONGYANG, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Pyongyang on Tuesday dismissed
the U.S. warning against its attempt to test-fire missiles and
said that the launch of a satellite or a missile is a "legitimate
right" of a sovereign state.
</P>
<P>
"Whether we will test-fire a satellite or a missile is a
legitimate right to be exercised by a sovereign state because it
in no way runs counter to the universally-accepted international
convention and the nuclear framework agreement between the
Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) and the United States,
" the Korean Central News Agency quoted a Foreign Ministry
spokesman as saying.
</P>
<P>
"The more the United States exerts pressure upon us, the
stronger our reaction will be," the spokesman said, adding that
this could lead to unpredictable consequences.
</P>
<P>
During his visit to Japan and South Korea last week, U.S.
Defense Secretary William Cohen warned the DPRK not to test-fire
missile and threatened to punish it if it did otherwise.
</P>
<P>
"If the United States returns challenge for our good faith,
that will force us to significantly increase our national defense
capabilities and continue to push ahead with the missile testfire,
to say nothing of satellite launch," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that Cohen is trying to find a pretext to ignite
a war by labeling DPRK's satellite efforts as missile test-fires.
</P>
</TEXT>
