<HEADLINE> World Bank Provides 182 Mln Dollar Loans for Vietnam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Two credit agreements on World Bank
(WB) development loans for Vietnam for the 1999 fiscal year,
totally worth more than 182 million U.S. dollars, were signed here
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Signatories were Le Duc Thuy, vice governor of the State Bank
of Vietnam, and WB resident representative Andrew Steer.
</P>
<P>
Under the two agreements, a project on irrigation development
in the Mekong Delta will receive a loan worth 101.86 million
dollars; and a project on hygienic improvement in Hai Phong, Da
Nang and Ha Long cities will be given a loan worth 80.5 million
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The irrigation project in the Mekong Delta will help develop
agriculture, improve the living conditions of and alleviate
poverty for people of Vinh Long, Tra Vinh, Can Tho, Kien Giang,
Soc Trang and Bac Lieu provinces.
</P>
<P>
The other project will improve services and upgrade
infrastructure facilities for urban environment in three cities of
Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
These two new agreements bring the World Bank's total loans for
Vietnam to more than 2.2 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
