<HEADLINE> Two Sentenced to Death for Invoice Fraud </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Two men convicted of issuing
fake value-added tax (VAT) invoices were sentenced to death
recently by the Shaoxing Intermediate People's Court of Zhejiang
Province.
</P>
<P>
Tang Weizhong, a manager of a Shenzhen-based company, and
Ouyang Hao, unemployed, were accused of issuing fake VAT invoices
involving a total of 400 million yuan (about 48 million U.S.
dollars), including 59 million yuan in tax revenue, in the 1996-
1997 period.
</P>
<P>
The court said that it was probable that only 1.7 million yuan
of the tax revenue could be retrieved, which meant enormous
economic losses for the country.
</P>
<P>
Three accomplices -- Xu Huahong, Jin Youxin and Sun Jinqun,
were respectively given life imprisonment and fixed-term
imprisonment of 14 years and 10 years.
</P>
<P>
Jin and Sun were also convicted of smuggling some 7,400 tons of
electrolytic copper and avoidance of 36.38 million yuan in tax.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990803.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Representative Explains China's Stance on Nuclear Disarmament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Zhu Shanqing, vice president of
Chinese People's Association for Peace and Disarmament, on Tuesday
expounded China's stance on nuclear disarmament at the opening day
of a three-day antinuclear conference in Hiroshima, western Japan.
</P>
<P>
"China has constantly adopted a responsible attitude on the
issue of nuclear disarmament," Zhu told the annual world
conference, hosted by the Japan Council Against A and H Bombs (
gensuikyo), a major antinuclear group in Japan.
</P>
<P>
First, China solemnly declared from the first day it possessed
nuclear weapons that it would not be the first to use such weapons
at any time and under any circumstances, Zhu elaborated.
</P>
<P>
China has also committed itself unconditionally not to use or
threaten to use nuclear weapons against non-nuclear-weapon states,
he said, adding that China is the only nuclear-weapon country that
has made and kept such a promise.
</P>
<P>
Second, Zhu went on to say, China has never deployed any
nuclear weapons outside its territories, and has never used or
threatened to use nuclear weapons against other countries.
</P>
<P>
Third, China has always exercised the utmost restraint in
developing nuclear weapons, both the number of nuclear tests
conducted by China and the quantity of nuclear weapons possessed
by the country are very limited, he said.
</P>
<P>
Fourth, Zhu pointed out, China has always vigorously supported
the efforts to relevant countries to establish nuclear-free zones
on the basis of voluntary consultation and agreement, and has
unconditionally pledged to provide the signatory states of nuclear-
free zones with security assurance.
</P>
<P>
Fifth, China has always been vigorously supporting the complete
prohibition and thorough destruction of nuclear weapons, he added.
</P>
<P>
On China's defense policy, Zhu stressed that China's national
defense policy is defensive in nature.
</P>
<P>
China does not seek hegemonism or engage in expansion, nor does
it station any troops abroad, go for military alliance or join
arms races, he said.
</P>
<P>
China's military expenditure has been kept at a fairly low
level, Zhu said, adding that China will further reduce its
military personnel by 500,000 by the end of the century, on the
basis of the reduction of one million in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
Zhu also said China is an important force for safeguarding
peace in Asia and the world as a whole, adding that the
development of China will only contribute to enhancing the trend
of mutual complementarity in the world, and promoting the common
development of all nations.
</P>
<P>
Zhu said the facts that the U.S.-led North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) used forces against Yugoslavia and attacked
the Chinese embassy there with missiles in May have manifested
that the U.S. hegemonism has undergone new development.
</P>
<P>
In an attempt to dominate the whole world, the U.S. is carrying
out the Two Ocean Strategies, namely the "Atlantic Ocean Strategy,
" which means to accelerate NATO's eastward expansion, and the "
Pacific Ocean Strategy," which is to strengthen the U.S.-Japan
military alliance, Zhu noted.
</P>
<P>
This has clearly proved that the U.S. has sped up the
implementation of its hegemonic policy, constituting a severe
threat to peace in Asia and the world at large, he said.
</P>
<P>
"In order to effectively safeguard peace in Asia and the world,
we must firmly oppose hegemonism," Zhu stressed.
</P>
<P>
The conference is the first of Gensuikyo's series of
antinuclear events until August 9 to observe the 54th anniversary
of the atomic bombing of Hiroshima and Nagasaki in 1945.
</P>
<P>
About 280 antinuclear activists, including 60 participants from
20 countries, are taking part in the conference.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Japan Congress Against A and H Bombs (Gensuikin),
another major antinuclear group in Japan, concluded its two-day
international conference in Hiroshima, after discussing ways to
create a nuclear free zone in Northeast Asia and to stop relying
on nuclear power. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990803.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Red Cross Evacuates Patients in Northern Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The Red Cross said Tuesday it had
evacuated eight patients in the last two days from areas held by
Tamil rebels in northern Sri Lanka following reports that four
people had died for lack of medicines.
</P>
<P>
The International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC) here said
it had arranged escorts for several boats to carry the sick to the
Mannar base hospital in northwestern Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
ICRC spokesman Harsha Gunawardena said its officials will visit
the Wanni area Thursday to transport another batch of seriously
ill patients.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the government said at least four sick people had
died due to the lack of urgent treatment in rebel-held Wanni
region.
</P>
<P>
The Sri Lankan Army Monday forwarded a new set of proposals to
the Tamil rebels through the ICRC to open a new route to Wanni
area as its earlier proposal was rejected by the rebels.
</P>
<P>
The government has traditionally supplied food and other items
to civilians in rebel-held areas, while allowing them access to
government-controlled towns for trade and other activities.
</P>
<P>
An earlier route was closed in May when the army launched a
fresh offensive in its war against the Tamil rebels, who have been
fighting for a separate homeland in Sri Lanka's north and east for
minority Tamils since 1983. 
</P>
