<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Belgium Denies Blocking Appointment of New NATO Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Belgium on Tuesday rejected news
reports that it had tried along with the Netherlands and
Luxembourg to block the appointment of British Defense Minister
George Robertson as the new chief of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
A Belgian Foreign Ministry Spokesman told Xinhua that Belgium
had no attempt to block such an appointment at a meeting of NATO
ambassadors here on Monday. The 19 representatives of NATO
members finished the meeting without reaching consensus on naming
Robertson as the successor to Spain's Javier Solana, the outgoing
NATO secretary-general.
</P>
<P>
According to the Dutch NOS radio, the three Benelux nations of
Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg were responsible for the
delay of the appointment process.
</P>
<P>
Spokesman for the Belgian Foreign Ministry, Hubert Cooreman,
said the ambassadors did not collectively endorse the British
nomination because some countries, including Belgium, the
Netherlands and Canada, had not received clear instructions from
their high-level authorities.
</P>
<P>
However, Cooreman said, his country was unhappy with the way
some big NATO members were operating on the timing of the decision
process. They decided the process without any consultation with
other smaller NATO countries, he said, stressing that they are
also full NATO members.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said Belgium did not consider the naming of a new
NATO chief as an urgent issue. Only last Friday did British Prime
Minister Tony Blair officially announce, in Sarajevo, the capital
of Bosnia-Herzegovina, the 53-year-old Robertson as Britain's NATO
chief candidate, he added.
</P>
<P>
"We are not disapproving Mr. Robertson's appointment. We are
just somewhat irritated by the way the big NATO members are doing,
" Cooreman said referring to the arrogant NATO members like the
United States and Britain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
