<DOCNO> XIE19990803.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trial of Cambodian KR leader Ta Mok To Be Delayed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Cambodian National Assembly's
Legislation Committee agreed Tuesday to submit a new law to the
assembly for final approval, paving the way for the delay of the
trial of captured Khmer Rouge leader Ta Mok.
</P>
<P>
The new law was proposed by the ruling Cambodian People's Party
(CPP) and the royalist FUNCINPEC party after a series of
discussion.
</P>
<P>
The new law states that "for the case of genocidal crimes, war
crimes, or crimes against humanity, the temporary detention can be
delayed once within every year, but the period of delay must not
exceed three years."
</P>
<P>
If the new law is approved by the National Assembly, Ta Mok
will not be tried next month for violating a 1994 law banning the
Khmer Rouge. Instead he will be tried only once under the law of
genocide.
</P>
<P>
Cambodia's military court has considered double trials if the
new law will not be passed.
</P>
<P>
Ta Mok's lawyer Benson Samay said last weekend that Ta Mok will
be tried late next month by the law outlawing the Khmer Rouge.
Under the current penal law of Cambodia, if the government does
not begin a trial before a six-month deadline, Ta Mok, arrested on
March 6, must be released in September.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Hun Sen and some Western analysts said earlier
that if Ta Mok were tried by the 1994 law, some current government
officials would be embarrassed for their collusion with Khmer
Rouge elements in the months leading to the July 1997 factional
fighting.
</P>
<P>
Cambodia has agreed to make a tribunal with international
standard in character in which foreign legal experts, prosecutors
and judges can take part. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
