<HEADLINE> More People in Beijing Using Lawsuits To Get Even </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The courts in Beijing have been
working hard to ensure the fairness of their verdicts and more
people are turning to the law to protect their rights.
</P>
<P>
In the first half of this year, courts at various levels in
Beijing heard 96,570 cases, up 32.9 percent from the same period
last year, according to the Municipal Higher People's Court.
</P>
<P>
Court statistics show 77,910 cases were concluded from January
to June this year, an increase of 36.2 percent over the first six
months of last year.
</P>
<P>
The increase is attributed to the rise in civil lawsuits and
instances of economic wrongdoing and mismanagement and it shows
that more people believe they can have their say by resorting to
the law, legal scholars say.
</P>
<P>
Since last year, Beijing's courts have held much more open
trials to ensure the fairness of their verdicts and to give people
greater confidence in the courts, scholars say.
</P>
<P>
To increase its transparency and to do a better job under
public scrutiny, Beijing's Intermediate Court No.1 has begun
giving people access to court documents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
