<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar's Foreign Trade Increases in Fiscal 1998-99 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar's foreign trade, including
 border trade, reached 3.995 billion U.S. dollars in fiscal
1998-99 which ended in March, up 16.67 percent from the previous
fiscal year's 3.424 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest economic indicators published by the
country's Central Statistical Organization, of the total trade
volume, imports were 2.815 billion dollars, while exports stood at
1.18 billion dollars, producing a trade deficit of 1.635 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar's import commodities are classified under the three
major categories of capital goods, consumers goods and
intermediate goods. The import value of the three sectors was
1.446 billion dollars, 1.039 billion dollars and 330 million
dollars respectively, accounting for 51.36 percent, 36.9 percent
and 11.74 percent of the total import correspondingly.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar's main export goods are agricultural products, marine
products such as fish and prawn, and forest products including
teak and hardwood.
</P>
<P>
The figures also indicate that Myanmar's private enterprises
are playing a key role in the country's foreign trade.
</P>
<P>
In 1998-99, the import value of the private sector made up
67.49 percent of the total import, while its export value
accounted for 69.31 percent of the total export.
</P>
<P>
The increase of Myanmar's foreign trade volume in the year was
closely linked with measures such as the simplification of import
and export formalities and the addition of border trade points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
