<HEADLINE> Poll Shows Most Canadians Brace for Common Currency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Most Canadians agree that there
will be a common North American currency in the next two decades,
according to the local media.
</P>
<P>
Citing a poll conducted by the Angus Reid Group between July 8
and 14, The Globe and Mail newspaper and CTV reported Tuesday that
approximately 77 percent of the interviewees believe a common
currency is likely in the next 20 years.
</P>
<P>
The media quoted the executive vice-president of the group
Darrell Bricker as declaring a momentum "proceeding apace" for
closer U.S.-Canadian economic ties.
</P>
<P>
Based on the poll of 1,500 Canadians, Bricker said "what all
this shows is that the move to integration is far stronger than
most people understand."
</P>
<P>
But the pollster admitted that 58 percent of those surveyed
still consider a common currency a "bad thing."
</P>
<P>
Discussion of a common currency in North America has
intensified this year in the wake of the move in January by 11
European nations to merge their currencies into the euro.
</P>
<P>
Canadian Prime Minister Jean Chretien, Finance Minister Paul
Martin and Bank of Canada governor Gordon Thiessen have all
rejected the concept of adopting the U.S. dollar or seeking a
currency union with the United States.
</P>
<P>
They argue that such a move would represent an unacceptable
loss of sovereignty for Canada, the local media said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
