<DOCNO> XIE19990803.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain's Pets to Get Passports to Travel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Britain on Tuesday outlined plans
to give pets passports to travel rather than lock them in kennels
for six months.
</P>
<P>
The move spells the beginning of the end for the quarantine
system and the passport was regarded as pets' passport to freedom.
</P>
<P>
At present, animals entering the United Kingdom have to spend
up to six months in quarantine to ensure they are not carrying
rabies before they are allowed to enter from rabies-free countries.
</P>
<P>
A BBC report quoted Baroness Hayman, junior minister at the
Ministry of Agriculture, Fisheries and Food, as saying that the
pilot schemes will begin operating from next year and will allow
pets identified by a microchip and certified free from rabies to
travel to and from UK without the usual stay in quarantine.
</P>
<P>
Microchips containing detailed information would sit under the
animal's skin.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that initial plans limiting the scheme to
those pets spending long periods abroad have been scrapped and pet
owners will be able to take their animals on day trips.
</P>
<P>
That scheme allows owners to take their pets abroad, even on
day trips, without having to put them in quarantine for six months
on their return.
</P>
<P>
"The new arrangements will keep Britain fully protected against
rabies while letting pet owners take their cat or dog abroad,"
Baroness Hayman said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990803.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Building Community Health Care System For Urbanites </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 3 (Xinhua) -- China plans to complete a
community-based health care system within a decade, to provide
convenient, economical and suitable medical services for urban
residents.
</P>
<P>
The massive plan, initiated by the Ministry of Health (MOH),
has won governmental backing, marked by an inter-departmental
announcement on developing urban community health care.
</P>
<P>
An MOH official said that he believed that, with the support of
the government, most urban Chinese will gradually be able to have
their ailments treated easily at home or at neighborhood clinics,
instead of having to queue at major hospitals.
</P>
<P>
"It is our goal to make medical service more accessible to,
inexpensive and effective for ordinary people by emphasizing the
role of the community," said Liu Keling, deputy director of the
Department of Community Health Care and Maternal and Child Health.
</P>
<P>
The official acknowledged that at present a large number of
urbanites are unable to enjoy convenient basic medical services,
since 80 percent of medical resources have been put into big
hospitals.
</P>
<P>
A survey of several provincial-level hospitals show that about
65 percent of 1,450 outpatient cases and 77 percent of 1,100
hospital admission cases are actually unnecessary, and can be
dealt with in local communities.
</P>
<P>
The community health care network will be composed of community
health care centers and stations, and general practitioners. The
services will be mainly provided to women, children and the
elderly, patients with chronic diseases and handicapped people.
</P>
<P>
Apart from treating illnesses, general practitioners are also
responsible for disease prevention, health promotion,
rehabilitation, health education and family planning services.
</P>
<P>
Liu Keling said that experiments are being carried out in some
70 cities, including Beijing, Shanghai and Tianjin. The nationwide
network is expected to be functional within the next ten years.
</P>
<P>
The MOH is considering establishing a series of standards and
regulations to monitor and control the service quality of
community health care, she noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990803.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Opposition Strike Ends in Bangladesh, 20 Injured </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 3 (Xinhua) -- A 30-hour countrywide strike
organized by Bangladesh's opposition alliance ended Tuesday,
during which nearly 20 people, including a policeman, were injured
and several activists were arrested for violence.
</P>
<P>
Life quickly returned to normal at noon with honking vehicles
back on the streets and full resumption of business activities all
over the capital.
</P>
<P>
Before the strike was over, large numbers of rickshaws and
auto-rickshaws and buses were seen moving at many places in the
capital.
</P>
<P>
During the strike, most shops along the main streets were
closed while most private offices were open in the morning and
financial institutions and banks continued operation.
</P>
<P>
Police said nearly 20 people were injured during the two-day
shutdown. But The New Nation newspaper reported over 300 people
were injured across the country Monday during the first day of the
stoppage, including some 50 in Dhaka and about 20 in Chittagong.
</P>
<P>
The Independent newspaper said about 50 persons were detained
Monday by police for "creating anarchy" and "damaging public
property."
</P>
<P>
About 5,000 riot police and paramilitary Bangladesh Rifle
forces were deployed at different important points in the capital,
and the ruling Awami League and its front organization brought out
anti-strike processions in the city to protest the strike.
</P>
<P>
The opposition alliance, comprising the Bangladesh Nationalist
Party, the Jatiya Party, the Jamaat-e-Islami and the Islami Oikya
Jote, started the strike, the eighth of its kind this year, to
protest against the government's decision last week giving
"corridor to India in the name of transshipment."
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a mass rally in northwestern Sirajganj district
Tuesday, Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina accused the opposition, by
calling the strike, of designing to destroy the prospects of
earning foreign exchange and creating jobs through the
transshipment facilities to India. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
