<HEADLINE> 50 Killed in Renewed Nigerian Ethnic Clash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 3 (Xinhua) -- At least 50 people were killed in
recent ethnic clashes in Nigeria's southwest Ondo state.
</P>
<P>
The death toll, caused by a renewed fighting erupted last week
between the Ilaje and Ijaw communities in Ondo Sate, was confirmed
by the delegates from both ethnic groups meeting at the state
governor's office Monday, the Daily Times newspaper reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Pastor Oyekan Arije, leader of the Ilaje delegates, said at the
 meeting that the trouble started when the Ijaws refused to vacate
villages and towns belonging to his people, which were taken over
during last year's crisis.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, Pere Camfo, president of the Ijaw National
Youth Council, accused the Ilaje youths of attacking the Ijaws and
trying to overrun Oroto and Ajapa in Ijaw kingdom. He threatened
an all-out war against the Ilajes if they do not stop their
killings.
</P>
<P>
State Governor Ade Adefarati had made a broadcast speech at the
 weekend calling on both sides to cease hostilities and embrace
dialog to resolve their differences.
</P>
<P>
The fight, in which sophisticated weapons were used, began at
an Ijaw town last week and spread quickly to other nearby
communities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
