<HEADLINE> New Infrastructure Projects Launched in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada Tuesday launched a group of new infrastructure projects
in Cebu, southern Philippines, in a bid to boost the economy
there.
</P>
<P>
The batch of projects worth 136 million pesos (3.4 million U.S.
dollars) are released for both Cebu city and Cebu province,
Philippine News Agency said.
</P>
<P>
Addressing an official gathering in the city of Cebu, Estrada,
who is paying a three-day visit there, said the money will fund
farm-to-market roads, bridges, hospitals and medical equipment and
waterworks systems.
</P>
<P>
The president said the farm-to-market roads and bridges are
necessary for farmers in far-flung areas to transport their
produce to the market. Waterworks projects, on the other hand,
will provide clean potable water to rural areas.
</P>
<P>
The newly-launched infrastructure projects, he said, are
manifestation of his administration's support to sustain Cebu's
economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Before his speech, agrarian reform officials distributed
certificates of land ownership to beneficiaries of the agrarian
reform program. 
</P>
