<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Machinery, Electronic Exports Grow in First Half Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
BEIJING, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Exports of Chinese machinery and
electronic products grew 9.7 percent to 33.26 billion U.S. dollars
in the first half of this year, according to the latest statistics
released by the General Administration of Customs.
</P>
<P>
Experts from the Customs' foreign trade department said that
the 10.4 percent growth of technology-extensive electronic goods,
machinery and instruments, accounting for 90 percent of machinery
and electronic exports, shows that the structure of exports of
such products has been further improved.
</P>
<P>
The statistics show that the exports of high-tech electronics,
aircraft, mobile phones and air-conditioners exceeded three fifths
of the total.
</P>
<P>
The export situation of state-run enterprises has taken a
favorable turn, while foreign-funded enterprises have maintained a
stable increase in exports of machinery and electronic goods.
</P>
<P>
Exports of machinery and electronic products to North America
maintained a high growth rate of 16.3 percent, while those to
Europe and Oceania grew by seven percent and 16 percent,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
China has boosted the amounts of such exports to Asia,
especially to the Republic of Korea and ASEAN countries, in the
same period. However, its exports to Africa and Latin America went
down 5.1 percent and 6.8 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
In the first half of this year, Shanghai, Jiangsu and Tianjin
witnessed a more than 20 percent growth in exports of machinery
and electronic products. Guangdong Province, which accounts for
half of China's exports of such products, enjoyed an increase
again after months of decline in such exports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
