<HEADLINE> Iraq Protests to U.N. over U.S.-British Bombardment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Iraq has protested against the
continuation of the U.S.-British warplanes bombardment of its
residential areas, killing civilians and destructing civil
facilities.
</P>
<P>
In a letter sent to U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan,
Iraq's Foreign Minister Mohammed Saeed al-Sahhaf demanded that
Annan intervene to stop such aggressive acts which scare
civilians and destroy public and private properties, the Iraqi
News Agency reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Sahhaf said that last Thursday and Friday, the U.S. and
Britain committed horrible crimes in northern and southern Iraq
in their bombardment of civil and service installations, which
killed 17 civilians and injured dozens of others.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the areas are vacant of any military target,
which means the bombing was basically aiming at causing more harm
to civilians and scaring them.
</P>
<P>
Those air attacks fully contradict the U.N. Charter and
international law and are flagrant violation of the sovereignty
of an independent state, he added.
</P>
<P>
Since the U.S. and Britain launched airstrikes against Iraq
last December, their warplanes have been regularly attacking Iraqi
military and civilian targets in no-fly zones, causing severe
civilian casualties and property damages.
</P>
<P>
"At a time Iraq condemns such recurrent criminal acts, it
demands you (Annan) intervene to the U.S. and Britain to stop
such acts," Sahhaf stressed.
</P>
<P>
The no-fly zones were imposed on Iraq by the U.S.-led western
allies following the 1991 Gulf War with the claimed aim of
protecting the Kurds in the north and the Shiite Muslims in the
south from possible attacks by the government troops.
</P>
<P>
Sahhaf said that Iraq holds all states either those who
launched the attacks or those countries from whose territories
the jet fighters take off such as Saudi Arabia, Kuwait and Turkey,
responsible for the damages Iraq sustained.
</P>
<P>
He affirmed that Iraq has firm right to compensation for the
damages it sustained due to such criminal acts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
