<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Factfile of Table Tennis Legend Xu Yinsheng </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
EINDHOVEN, Netherlands, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Chinese table tennis
legend Xu Yinsheng said he didn't want to seek re-election at the ITTF
Congress here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Following is factfile of Xu Yinsheng
</P>
<P>
1938 -- Born in Shanghai;
</P>
<P>
1956 -- member of the Shanghai table tennis team, then national team
member;
</P>
<P>
1959 -- As the youngest of the Chinese team, he competed in the
25th World Table Tennis Championships in Dortmund, Germany;
</P>
<P>
1960 -- Men's singles runner-up in the Chinese national
championships;
</P>
<P>
1961 -- Member of the champion team in the 26th World Table
Tennis Championships, third-place in the men's singles;
</P>
<P>
1963 -- Member of the champion team in the 27th World Table
Tennis championships;
</P>
<P>
1965 -- Member of the champion team in the 28th World Table
Tennis Championships, winning the men's doubles with Zhuang Zedong;
</P>
<P>
1966 -- Coach of the Chinese national team;
</P>
<P>
1970 -- Head coach of the Chinese national team;
</P>
<P>
1971 -- Led his team to win the men's team title in the 31th
World Table Tennis Championships;
</P>
<P>
1973 -- Led his team to the men's team second place in the
32th World Table Tennis Championships;
</P>
<P>
1977 -- Vice Chairman of the Chinese Physical Culture and Sports
Commission;
</P>
<P>
1979 -- President of the Chinese Table Tennis Association;
</P>
<P>
1981 -- Vice President of the International Table Tennis
Federation;
</P>
<P>
1996 -- President of the International Table Tennis Federation;
</P>
<P>
1999 -- Hononary President of the International Table Tennis
Federation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
