<HEADLINE> Palestinians Reject Putting off Wye Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinians have categorically
rejected an Israeli proposal to put off the implementation of the
Wye Accord and to combine part of the agreement with the final
status talks.
</P>
<P>
Secretary General of the Palestine Liberation Organization
Executive Committee Mahmoud Abbas said there was no justification
for delaying troops withdrawal for several months, Voice of
Palestine radio reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Abbas, who is also known as Abu Mazen, made the remarks in
response to Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak's proposal to start
the remaining two stages of troops withdrawal on October 1.
</P>
<P>
The three-stage troops withdrawal from another 13.1 percent of
the West Bank stipulated under the Wye Accord should have been
finished by the end of January. But the agreement was suspended in
early December by former Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu only
after the first-stage pullout.
</P>
<P>
Abbas expressed astonishment that the ruling Israeli Labor
Party, which had opposed Netanyahu's delay in enforcing the Wye
agreement, was now attempting to delay and evade the firm and
complete implementation of the agreement with the pretext of
integrating certain articles with the final settlement
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Abbas pointed out that Palestinians demand adamantly
enforcement of the Wye accord in letter and spirit.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians, he added, were not in favor of introducing
any amendments, postponement or integration as proposed by the
Israeli government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
