<HEADLINE> Nigerian Senator President Urged to Clear Charges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Many Nigerian senators have
required Senate President Evan Enwerem to clear himself of the
allegations of the unclean past and even "step aside" to allow
unbiased probe.
</P>
<P>
The Ebwerem's strait came only two weeks after the resignation
of the country's former speaker of the House of Representatives
Alhaji Buhari over allegations of perjury and forgery, the
Guardian newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The current edition of the "Tell" magazine shocked the west
African country's capital Monday by accusing Enwerem of an alleged
criminal conviction.
</P>
<P>
The lawmakers severally discussed the publication in tones that
suggest a determination to have the senate president clear himself
of the allegations as the National Assembly resumes Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Senate leader Abdallah Wali however, declined to comment on the
 allegation Monday, but sources hinted of a likelihood of the
legislators discussing the issue at caucus levels before it gets
to the chamber.
</P>
<P>
While Enwerem was being expected Monday from his Imo State home
where he was accorded a civic reception at the weekend, some
senators who had arrived in Abuja got concerned that an
explanation would be desirable in the interest of credibility of
the National Assembly.
</P>
<P>
Senator Adamu Fanda said: "We at the House of Representatives
will move a motion calling for the establishment of a communique
of the House of Representatives that will look into the veracity
of these allegations raised against the senate president.
</P>
<P>
"We are making this for two reasons. First, in any joint
session of the National Assembly, it is the president of the
Senate that presides. So invariably, he is our leader. Secondly,
we have the right as members of the National Assembly to
investigate everything that happens in this country," he
explained.
</P>
<P>
There was also concern in the ruling People's Democratic Party
(PDP) circles over the publication Monday. A senior party member
said: "We said it earlier that if this matter is true, he should
resign on health grounds. But he has denied it. Let's see how it
goes."
</P>
<P>
At a civic reception held for him at Owerri at the weekend,
Enwerem had warned against a smear campaign which he alleged was
being mounted against him. "Be on the look out and watch for
this and be assured that all blackmail against me is false," He
alerted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
