<HEADLINE> Situation in Namibia's Caprivi Still Tense </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The situation in the Caprivi
region in northeastern Namibia remained tense Tuesday after
Monday's violent clashes between government forces and
secessionists, South African Press Association reported.
</P>
<P>
Schools and Businesses remained closed Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Major-General Martin Shalli, chief of staff of the Namibian
Defense Force (NDF), said his force was "busy with the clean-up
operation until further notice."
</P>
<P>
Namibian President Sam Nujoma declared late Monday an
indefinite state of emergency in Caprivi's main town of Katima
Mulilo.
</P>
<P>
The state of emergency effectively gives security agencies the
power to maintain law and order by limiting people's freedom of
movement until the operation of "cleaning up" the rebels was
completed.
</P>
<P>
In a televised speech to the nation Monday, Nujoma said five
police officers, three NDF members and five rebels had been killed
in the skirmishes which started in the early hours of Monday.
</P>
<P>
Gabriel Mwalima, son-in-law of rebel leader Mashake Muyongo,
was among eight members of the Caprivi Liberation Army arrested in
the clashes.
</P>
<P>
There had been sporadic gunfire through the night in Katima
Mulilo, South African Broadcasting Corporation correspondent John
Grobler said in a radio interview Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
