<DOCNO> XIE19990803.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inflation Falls to 7.7 Percent in Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania's overall
inflation maintained its downward trend, falling to 7.7 percent
in June from 8.1 percent in July, an economic report issued by
the central bank has said.
</P>
<P>
The decrease is partly explained by low prices recorded in
several food items like rice, maize, beans, beef and soft drinks,
the Bank of Tanzania said in its latest monthly economic review
available Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The bank noted that the rate of inflation was slightly below
the set target of 7.5 percent, but is hopeful to reach five
percent by June, 2000 in view of the improving food supply
situation, coupled with the implementation of prudent monetary
and fiscal policies.
</P>
<P>
During the month, food situation in the country improved due to
the ongoing harvest season. By the end of June, the Strategic
Grain Reserve stock reached 22,929.8 tons, representing an
increase of 42.8 percent from the stocks in May.
</P>
<P>
In another development, the report said Tanzania's total
external debt arrived at 7.97 billion U.S. dollars, decreasing 0.6
percent from the previous month.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
