<HEADLINE> Nigeria Committed to Eradicating Campus Cultism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian Education Minister Tunde
Adeniran has declared that the federal government would not extend
the three-month ultimatum given vice-chancellors and other heads
of tertiary institutions to stamp out campus cultism in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Adeniran who spoke in Ibadan, capital of Nigeria's western Oyo
state over the weekend, said the government had carried out its
independent investigation and was sure that the menace could be
eradicated within the stipulated time if the authorities of the
institutions committed themselves to doing it, the Guardian
newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Although the minister declined comments on what reprisals
awaited university authorities if they failed in the mission, he
declared that "the three-month deadline is very, very feasible."
</P>
<P>
Two weeks ago, the government read the riot act to university
authorities after the gruesome murder of seven students of the
Obafemi Awolowo University, Ile-Ife by suspected cult members.
</P>
</TEXT>
