<HEADLINE> Share Prices Close Higher on Singapore Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Selective buying of finance
stocks brought the key Straits Times Index (STI) up although share
prices were broadly lower on the Singapore Stock Market Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark STI rebounded by 14.72 points to end at 2,143.37,
nearly offsetting the 17.12-point fall Monday.
</P>
<P>
The total volume contracted to 220.22 million shares worth
467.37 million Singapore dollars (277.70 million U.S. dollars).
Falls outnumbered rises by 226 to 77 with 141 counters unchanged.
</P>
<P>
DelMonte remained at top of the volume list with a turnover of
14.62 million shares. It was followed by Aztech which had 14.39
million units done. AFP was the next with 10.54 million counters
changing hands.
</P>
<P>
DBS F topped the actives chart as it surged up 90 cents to
close at 22.00 Singapore dollars. SPH and Venture climbed up 80
cents to finish at 30.60 and 14.80 Singapore dollars respectively.
SPH 100 picked up 60 cents to end at 30.60 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, Creative 50 was the biggest loser of the day,
dropping 50 cents to close at 17.70 Singapore dollars. PacCent
shed 40 cents to finish at 5.80 Singapore dollars. Asean sank 25
cents to end at 9.00 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
Brokers noted that electronic stocks were higher after the
Natsteel Electronics Monday reported strong profit growth for the
first half of 1999.
</P>
<P>
They also said the bank shares were trading stronger led by the
DBS local and foreign shares and OCBC F.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said as there are little fresh leads to encourage the
market sentiment, investors remained largely passive and many are
waiting for more corporate earning results before venturing back.
</P>
<P>
Worries about a possible interest-rate hike continued to be a
factor keeping institutional investors on the sidelines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
