<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Man Gets Prison Sentence For Copyright Infringement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, August 3 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese man has become the
first person in China to be sentenced to jail and fined for
software copyright infringement.
</P>
<P>
Wang Antao, a partner of the Hangzhou Honghan Software Co. Ltd.,
was given 4 years in jail, fined 20,000 yuan and ordered to pay
the plaintiff 286,900 yuan in compensation by the Xiacheng
District People's Court in the city of Hangzhou, the capital of
Zhejiang Province.
</P>
<P>
Wang was a salesman at the Hangzhou Tianli Consulting and
Engineering Co., the plaintiff in the case. He bought an illegal
copy of a water supply control system developed by Tianli from
another employee last year and had the copy slightly altered and
renamed and sold it to 4 waterworks for more than 200,000 yuan in
all.
</P>
<P>
When a study of the copies found them to be fundamentally the
same as the original, the court ruled that Wang had committed the
crime of copyright infringement.  
</P>
</TEXT>
