<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian President Holds Informal Meeting With Major Political Parties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President B.J. Habibie
Tuesday held an informal meeting with leaders of political parties
which won seats in the House of Representatives and the General
Elections Commission (KPU) leaders.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Habibie said he has approved the results of
the vote count finalized by the Indonesian Election Committee
(PPI) on July 15.
</P>
<P>
The head of state said the reform agenda should run smoothly as
mandated by the People's Consultative Assembly (MPR) during its
special session late last year.
</P>
<P>
"There is the main agenda of reform that should be carried out.
Thus in this forum, as mandated by the MPR special session in
1998, I declare that the results of the vote count are valid," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Stressing that the MPR gave him the mandate and responsibility
to carry out the general election, Habibie said he wants to see
the agenda implemented on schedule.
</P>
<P>
Habibie further said that the MPR's general session later this
year could not be postponed.
</P>
<P>
"A postponement would only draw various interpretations and
speculations," he said.
</P>
<P>
The MPR, the country's highest decision-making body, will meet
in November to elect the country's next president.
</P>
<P>
On the general election, Habibie acknowledged that it had some
weaknesses, but said they were not substantial.
</P>
<P>
He urged officials involved in the implementation of the
election to take legal measures against election violations.
</P>
<P>
"It is necessary to settle the problems so they will not become
bad examples for the next election," he said.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was attended by National Awakening Party Chairman
Matori Abdul Jalil, Crescent and Star Party Chairman Jusril Ihza
Mahendra, Golkar Party Chairman Akbar Tanjung and other political
party leaders.
</P>
<P>
Chairwoman of the Indonesian Democratic Party of Struggle
(PDI-P) Megawati Soekarnoputri and General Chairman of the
National Mandate Party (PAN) Amien Rais did not attend the
informal meeting.
</P>
<P>
The PPI concluded the vote count on July 15, giving the bulk of
the 462 seats at stake to five major parties. The main opposition
PDI-P won with 33.74 percent of votes, outnumbering the ruling
Golkar Party, which trailed with 22.44 percent.
</P>
<P>
Trailing in third place is the National Awakening Party with
12.61 percent, followed by the United Development Party (10.71
percent) and PAN (7.12 percent).
</P>
<P>
According to calculations by national newspapers, PDI-P is
expected to get 154 seats in the House of Representatives and
Golkar 120. Many of the smaller parties will not gain any seats in
the new parliament.
</P>
<P>
Forty-eight political parties took part in the election to
compete for 462 of the 500 seats in the House of Representatives
(DPR). The remaining 38 seats are reserved for the military, whose
members do not vote. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
