<HEADLINE> Singapore Parliament Laments First Lady's Death, Defers MPs' Questions Over President's Remarks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Singapore's parliament Tuesday
lamented the death of the country's First Lady Mrs. Ong Teng
Cheong and deferred MPs' questions over remarks by the president
two weeks ago about problems with the government.
</P>
<P>
At Tuesday's sitting, the parliament observed a two-minute
silence in memory of the first lady on a special motion by Prime
Minister Goh Chok Tong to express condolences to President Ong and
his family.
</P>
<P>
Goh said the president had lost his dear wife and the hearts of
Singaporeans went out to him.
</P>
<P>
Parliament members from both the ruling and opposition parties
and of different ethnic origins spoke in praise of Mrs. Ong's
virtue of unfailing kindness and graciousness to others, her
bravery in fighting the illness and her dedication to her family,
the people and the country.
</P>
<P>
Mrs. Ong died of colon cancer last Friday after a two-and-half
years' battle with the disease and her body was cremated Tuesday
afternoon with a long procession attending the funeral.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the parliament deferred to a later sitting an oral
answer to questions by MPs on remarks by the president at his July
16 news conference.
</P>
<P>
At the press conference President Ong Teng Cheong, while
announcing he would not run for another presidential term, talked
about problems with the government as he tried to define his role
as guardian of the country's reserves.
</P>
<P>
Financial Minister Richard Hu, speaking on behalf of the prime
minister, affirmed that the government was going to make a
ministerial statement on the issue.
</P>
<P>
But the ministerial statement was postponed in view of the
death of Mrs. Ong.
</P>
<P>
Hu asked the speaker of the parliament to defer the MPs'
questions until after the issuing of the statement so that the
comments could be put in their proper context. 
</P>
</TEXT>
