<HEADLINE> Philippines Declares State of Calamity in Flooded Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada declared Tuesday a state of calamity in Metro Manila and
the provinces of Pangasinan, Pampanga and Rizal following flash
floods induced by massive downpour since Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The president made the declaration in Cebu during his ongoing
three-day visit to inaugurate vital infrastructure projects. He
urged all government agencies concerned to ensure the safety of
residents in the affected areas.
</P>
<P>
Flash floods brought about by two-day torrential rains starting
Sunday hit Metro Manila and nearby provinces, killing at least 19
people, submerging 180 villages and forcing more than 3,000
families to evacuate.
</P>
<P>
"All departments and other government agencies concerned are
hereby directed to implement and execute relief and rehabilitation
work in accordance with existing operational plans, directives and
orders issued in connection with calamities," Estrada said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Tuesday, Estrada said that government agencies have
been mobilized in massive and concerted efforts to provide
assistance to residents in Metro Manila and the rest of Luzon
Island affected by the monsoon-triggered floods.
</P>
<P>
He ordered the government bodies to coordinate search, rescue
and relief operations, and safeguard the properties of residents
who abandoned flooded homes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
