<HEADLINE> Nigeria, Libya Join Hands to Resolve Conflicts in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria and Libya will coordinate
their position on the forthcoming special summit of the
Organization of African Unity (OAU) in a bid to make the African
continent conflict-free by next year.
</P>
<P>
After delivering a special message from Libyan leader Muammar
Gaddafi to President Olusegun Obasanjo, Libyan special envoy Ali
Abdulsalami Tureki said Monday that Libya is willing to work with
Nigeria in the resolution of conflicts within the African
continent.
</P>
<P>
"We had worked in the past with Nigeria when President
(Olusegun) Obasanjo was in office to solve the Chadian problems,
we worked in Angola and now we decided to also work together to
end the African conflicts," said the Libyan envoy.
</P>
<P>
Libya is scheduled to host the OAU special summit in September,
which is designed to review sections of the organization's charter
to bring it in line with present realities.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian Foreign Minister Alhaji Sule Lamido held discussions
with the Libyan envoy in capital Abuja Monday on ways of resolving
outstanding conflicts in the continent, the New Nigerian newspaper
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Following the discussions, the visiting envoy who is Libya's
minister of African affairs, said, "we discussed the various
conflicts in the continent including Sierra Leone, Congo and
Angola."
</P>
<P>
Both countries shared the same commitment to making the
continent conflict-free by next year, he said.
</P>
<P>
During the OAU summit held last month in Algiers, Nigerian
President Obasanjo suggested that next year should be the year of
peace in Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
