<HEADLINE> Kenyan Police Arrest Bhang Suspects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Anti-narcotics police have
arrested 20 suspects who were transporting 120 stones of bhang in
Nakuru town, the capital of Rift Valley Province in Central Kenya.
</P>
<P>
The suspects who were arrested over the weekend also
transported almost 1,000 liters of illegal chang'aa (a kind of
traditionally-brew liquor), according to Nakuru Police Chief
Andrew Kimoetto.
</P>
<P>
The East African Standard newspaper quoted the police chief as
saying that the suspects were flushed out of the public transport
vehicles along the Nakuru-Nairobi Highway.
</P>
<P>
The police boss said the officers stopped the vehicles at
random and found the contraband cargo being ferried to Nairobi,
the capital of Kenya.
</P>
<P>
Kimoetto also said that on Friday night, the police also netted
365 liters of chang'aa and held 10 suspects in connection with the
illicit brew, adding that another suspect was arrested as he tried
to ferry 72 stones of bhang to Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the police in Kenya's Eastern Province discovered
more than 1, 500 acres of land are under bhang plantations in
Mount Kenya forest as police are intensifying operations to rid
the forest of drug farms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
