<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Many New Zealand Students Skip Breakfast: Surveys </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, August 3 (Xinhua) -- An alarming third of New
Zealand teenagers are going to school without breakfast, the most
important meal of the day, with the worst offenders being girls,
according to two surveys which were released here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The surveys show that 76,000 children aged between 13 and 17
skip breakfast because they don't have enough time or they just
don't feel like it.
</P>
<P>
New Zealand's leading dietitian and nutritionist Jeni Pearce
said in the surveys that the high level of breakfast skipping
among youngsters should be of great concern to parents, teachers
and children themselves.
</P>
<P>
The surveys, she said, clearly indicate "there is a lack of
understanding and a large amount of misinformation among
adolescents about the importance of breakfast for optimum mental
and physical development."
</P>
<P>
"Breakfast is the one meal of the day that should not be
skipped, especially by growing teenagers.
</P>
<P>
"Breakfast kick-starts the brain and improves mental and
physical performance and actually helps maintain a healthy body
weight," Pearce said.
</P>
<P>
The results of the surveys came from 299 interviews with
adolescents aged 13 to 17 years. Questionnaires were also sent to
every school principals in New Zealand, asking them why they
thought their students were skipping breakfast and what they
thought the main effects were.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
