<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Intel Develops New Processors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Intel Corporation Monday
introduced two new processors, one for mainstream computing and
the other for low-end personal computers.
</P>
<P>
The chip giant, which has been embracing the Internet and
fighting for both high- and low-end market, said that the Pentium
III processor 600 MHz was developed for powerful Internet and
mainstream computing, and the Celeron processor was for PCs priced
around 1,000 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Pentium III processor 600 MHz delivers Intel's highest
levels of performance, longevity and investment protection for
today's and tomorrow's computing needs, the company said.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Forbes earlier this year, Intel CEO Craig
Barrett revealed his company's strategy of developing networking
chips, which fall into three functional categories. Interface
chips connect networking gear to the information umbilical cord of
fiber or copper. Processing chips act on the data directly by
deciphering, for instance, whether data are coming or going.
</P>
<P>
And controller chips help manage how a company network
functions by setting such policies as whose bits have top priority
and which data need special protection. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
