<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Rebound in Tokyo on Stronger Dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices rebounded in Tokyo
Tuesday on buying led by export-oriented high-tech issues after
the U.S. dollar rose against the yen late in the day.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange rose 144.23 points, or 0.81
percent from Monday's close to end at 17,969.93.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index, covering all First
Section issues, gained 13.37 points or 0.91 percent to 1,481.99.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section went up to an estimated 490.48
million shares from Monday's 436.76 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Fujitsu continued leading the market in terms of volume.
</P>
<P>
The dollar's surge against the yen boosted stock prices just
before the market closed, traders said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. currency was trading at 115.47-50 yen at 3 p.m. in
Tokyo, up from 114.80-83 yen at 9 a.m.
</P>
<P>
Comments by Japanese Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa that he
and U.S. Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers agreed to keep in
close touch with each other over the currency movements drove the
dollar higher, traders said.
</P>
<P>
Of the issues listed on the First Section, losers exceeded
gainers 652 to 554, with 114 issues ending unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
