<HEADLINE> U.N., Red Cross Resume Flights to Kabul: Reports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations and the
International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC) on Tuesday resumed
flights to the Afghan capital of Kabul, reports reaching here
said.
</P>
<P>
Two planes respectively belonging to the United Nations and the
ICRC landed at the city's airport early in the morning, bringing
relief and aid workers from neighboring Pakistan, the reports
said.
</P>
<P>
The resumption of the aid flights came at a time when the
ruling Taliban is driving opposition forces from the capital's
outskirts.
</P>
<P>
International relief flights to Kabul were canceled last week
after anti-Taliban groups headed by former defense minister Ahmad
Shah Masood fired rockets at the airport when a U.N. plane was to
land. 
</P>
