<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia's Tourist Arrivals Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Australia's tourist arrivals in
the first half of 1999 rose six percent over the same period of
1998 due largely to better financial times in Asia, a senior
official said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Australia Tourist Commission Chief John Morse said the
half-yearly rise showed the industry was bouncing back.
</P>
<P>
Morse said in a statement that arrivals out of the
financially-embattled Asia showed bullish growth.
</P>
<P>
Arrivals from Indonesia from January to the end of June are up
nearly 18 percent on last year, South Korea is up an
"extraordinary" 87 percent, Malaysia up 30 percent and Thailand "a
very pleasing" 49 percent, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, key traditional market regions such as Europe and
the Americas both recorded very healthy growth, up 7.6 percent and
10.6 percent respectively, he said.
</P>
<P>
"And arrivals from New Zealand, Australia's second largest
market, rose a creditable 3.2 percent on the same period in 1998,"
Morse added.
</P>
<P>
The only cloud over the figures was provided by Australia's
largest market, Japan, which fell 5.5 percent despite a recent
economic upturn, he said.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary data released on Tuesday by the Australian Bureau
of Statistics showed that in June 1999, 368,600 short-term
visitors arrived in Australia, a seasonally adjusted decline of
1,200 on the previous month.
</P>
<P>
The bureau's figures also showed a nine percent increase in the
number of young Australians aged between 18 and 34 travelling
overseas for holidays in 1998 compared to 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
