<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam to Have Stricter Control of CDs, Cassettes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam is to make more efforts to
crack down on the illegal trading, production and reproduction of
compact disc (CD) and cassettes.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam's Ministry of Culture and Information is expected to
issue new rules next month to restore order to the chaotic
audio-video cassette tape and compact disc (CD) market, according
to a report of Vietnam's English business newspaper The Saigon
Times Daily on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Performance Arts Department of Vietnam's Ministry of
Culture and Information would supervise the production, trading,
import and distribution of tapes and CDs, said the director of the
ministry's Law Department.
</P>
<P>
The department would seal stamps on products whose content is
not prohibited. After this, the products could be distributed
without having to go through censorship agencies.
</P>
<P>
Only businesses licensed to operate in this sector can import
audio-video tapes and CDs. And this still requires permission from
the ministry's Planing Department or city or provincial culture
and information authorities.
</P>
<P>
More than 20,000 illicit audio-video tapes and CDs have been
seized since the country launched a campaign on July 24 to crack
down on the illegal trading, production and reproduction of these
items. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
