<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 09:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel, PNA to Coordinate Millennium Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Israel and the Palestinian
National Authority (PNA) are planning a joint campaign to prepare
for the expected flood of pilgrims at Christian sites during the
millennium year.
</P>
<P>
Israeli officials are concerned about the overcrowding at the
most popular sites, like the Church of the Holy Sepulcher in
Jerusalem, the Church of the Nativity in Bethlehem, and the
baptismal sites along the Jordan River, local daily The Jerusalem
Post said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"We have prepared plans for tourists to visit other places
besides these three," said Shlomo Dror, spokesman for the
government coordinator of activities in the territories.
</P>
<P>
The idea is to set up alternative tourist attractions aimed at
siphoning off the crowds as they travel through the Holy Land.
</P>
<P>
Until now, eight joint committees have been set up to deal with
the tourism coordination between Israel and the PNA.
</P>
<P>
These include committees on transportation, crossing points,
hotels, joint marketing, and safety and rescue. They are expected
to convene shortly.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, PNA Minister of Tourism Mitri Abu Aytah said
that the problem is not a paucity of sites but a lack of hotel
rooms.
</P>
<P>
"We have hundreds of tourist sites. That is not the
question. We have to develop our hotel capacity. We are expecting
a lot of people, and we hope that we will be able to work
together with the Israelis on this," Aytah said.
</P>
<P>
Israeli officials expect some 4 million tourists next year, who
will visit Christian sites in Israel or Palestinian-controlled
areas.
</P>
<P>
"We don't have enough rooms and there will be great traffic
jams. If we can't coordinate with the Palestinians, we will be in
trouble and the tourists will flee," Dror said.
</P>
<P>
Dror noted that just trying to coordinate the flow of buses
between Israel and the Palestinian-controlled areas was a
logistical challenge.
</P>
<P>
"We need to find other places for the tourists to go, so they
won't just be standing around," Dror said.
</P>
<P>
Israeli officials are also expecting a mammoth list of
dignitaries, state leaders, and even the pope to converge on the
Holy Land. One entrepreneur has even said he is planning to bring
the world's greatest tenors here for a gala concert transmitted
around the world.
</P>
<P>
"It's going to be an intense year," Dror said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990803.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong-bound Foodstuff Safe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Foodstuff shipped to Hong Kong
from the mainland via Shenzhen in Guangdong Province is perfectly
safe - this was the message at a recent conference on food safety
in Shenzhen, next door to Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Food safety was thrust into the limelight on the international
stage because of the mad cow disease and dioxin contamination of
meat.
</P>
<P>
In the first six months of the year, the Shenzhen Commodity
Inspection Bureau examined 5,427 tons of milk, 20,025 tons of live
poultry, and 45,710 tons of fresh vegetables bound for Hong Kong,
worth more than 24 million U.S. dollars in all.
</P>
<P>
No food hygiene problems had been reported, the conference was
told. 
</P>
</TEXT>
