<HEADLINE> China's Armed Police Say They're Ready To Fight Floods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of China's Armed Police
are prepared to fight possible floods this summer, according to
the State Flood Control and Drought Relief Headquarters.
</P>
<P>
A source there said that more than ten thousand armed policemen
are fighting floodwaters along the Yangtze River. This summer,
heavy rains have hit many parts of central China, causing flooding
on the Yangtze and nearby lakes.
</P>
<P>
Armed police in Hubei, Hunan, Anhui, and Zhejiang provinces
were sent to flood areas where they helped move more than 1,000
people and 30 million tons of materials. So far this year, about
140,000 armed policemen have been involved in flood fighting at
various times in different parts of the country, many of whom have
worked for weeks without stop.
</P>
<P>
Armed police stationed along the Yellow, Huaihe, and Songhua
rivers have set up flood-fighting headquarters in their respective
areas with flood-fighting materials and some units are helping
local people patrol levees where the water is above the danger
level. 
</P>
</TEXT>
