<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Namibia Declares State of Emergency in Caprivi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Namibian President Sam
Nujoma declared late Monday a state of emergency, including a
dusk-to-dawn curfew, in the Caprivi region where fighting erupted
between secessionists and government forces.
</P>
<P>
By late Monday, the revolt, which erupted in the remote town of
Katima Mulilo near the borders with Botswana and Zambia, appeared
to have been quelled, South Africa's The Star daily reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Rebel troops, reportedly supported by the Angolan rebel
movement National Union for the Total Independence of Angola
(UNITA), were reported to be retreating toward Zambia.
</P>
<P>
The bodies of three Namibian Defense Force soldiers, two police
officers and three rebels from the so-called Caprivi Liberation
Army were due to be airlifted to Windhoek late Monday night, said
the paper.
</P>
<P>
It quoted eyewitnesses as saying that, however, there were
nearly 20 bodies, including those of civilians, at the scenes of
the battle in the business center and the nearby airport.
</P>
<P>
In a televised address to the nation, Nujoma said Namibian
forces were under strict orders to leave no stone unturned in
ensuring that peace and tranquillity returned to the Caprivi.
</P>
<P>
Nujoma said a "mop-up operation" was under way in the troubled
strip. He also announced that the building of the Namibian
Broadcasting Corporation (NBC) and other government buildings,
which the rebels have attempted to take over, had been fully
"liberated".
</P>
<P>
Eyewitnesses said rebels began the revolt with an attack on the
police station at Katima Mulilo shortly after 2 a.m. (0000 GMT)
Monday, shooting dead two officers and wounding four others.
</P>
<P>
An attempt to capture Mpacha airport, 20 kilometers outside the
town, was foiled by government troops.
</P>
<P>
Police and the army stormed the rebel-held NBC offices and
threw in mortars and tear gas before taking control.
</P>
<P>
Business in the town stopped and schools were closed
indefinitely while hundreds of residents huddled down, trapped in
their shops and offices as bullets and larger munitions flew
across the street.
</P>
<P>
Late Monday, the government claimed the rebels were retreating
toward the Zambian border north of the town, but some
secessionists were understood to be still holed up in the town,
the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The rebels are believed to be Caprivi secessionists led by
exiled former Democratic Turnhalle Alliance leader Mishake
Muyongo.
</P>
<P>
Muyongo, together with 11 other secessionist leaders, fled to
neighboring Botswana in October. They were granted asylum in
February this year and were later resettled in Denmark.
</P>
<P>
Some 2,500 people also crossed into Botswana last year,
claiming to be fleeing in order to avoid harassment by the
Namibian authorities. Hundreds of them have been repatriated
voluntarily to Namibia after being granted asylum. 
</P>
</TEXT>
