<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian President Endorses Poll Results </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President B.J. Habibie
Tuesday endorsed the final results from the June 7 parliamentary
election, saying the delay in endorsing the results will cause
many problems.
</P>
<P>
He said the signatories of the final tally had represented 95
percent of the total vote.
</P>
<P>
Habibie took the move after the General Elections Commission
(KPU) failed to meet its deadline for endorsing the results of the
general election.
</P>
<P>
On July 26, 27 of the 48 political parties at the KPU refused
to sign off on the final tally, saying the elections were unfair.
They cited more than 100,000 alleged irregularities in defense of
their decision.
</P>
<P>
Another 17 political parties, including all five major parties,
accepted the tally, while four abstained.
</P>
<P>
The 1999 law on general elections stipulates that elections can
only be considered valid if the results are accepted by at least
two-thirds of the 53 KPU members, which include representatives
from the 48 political parties and five government representatives.
</P>
<P>
Under these circumstances, the KPU has submitted the election
results to the president for a solution. Habibie later handed over
the case to the Election Supervisory Committee (Panwaslu) for
verification, ruling that Panwaslu would be given seven days to
finish the job.
</P>
<P>
Twelve parties have submitted their reasons for refusing to
approve the elections results until the deadline on July 29, but
others failed to do the same. The Indonesian National Party led by
Supeni and the New Indonesia Party changed their mind and signed
the poll results on Monday.
</P>
<P>
After studying those reasons, Panwaslu concluded that none of
the parties' objections were valid and reported this to Habibie
who then returned the documents to the KPU along with the
committee's call for the KPU to endorse and declare the poll's
outcome.
</P>
<P>
Ryaas Rasyid, the government liaison officer with the KPU who
is also the director-general at the Home Affairs Ministry, said
that although the president has the constitutional basis to
validate the final tally following the recommendation of Panwaslu,
he has referred it back to the KPU to declare the election
results.
</P>
<P>
But, in its plenary session here on Monday, the KPU again
failed to endorse the poll results. The meeting turned chaotic and
was adjourned following a heated debate between KPU government
representatives and party representatives over the results of
Panwaslu's investigation.
</P>
<P>
On June 7, over 110 million Indonesians cast their votes in the
country's first democratic poll since 1955. But the count has been
beset with delays.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian Election Committee (PPI) has concluded the vote
count on July 15, giving the bulk of the 462 seats at stake to
five major parties. The main opposition Indonesian Democratic
Party of Struggle (PDI-P) won with 33.74 percent of the vote,
outnumbering the ruling Golkar Party, which trailed with 22.44
percent.
</P>
<P>
Trailing in third place is the National Awakening Party with
12.61 percent, followed by the United Development Party (10.71
percent) and the National Mandate Party (7.12 percent).
</P>
<P>
According to calculations by national newspapers, PDI-P is
expected to get 154 seats of the House of Representatives and
Golkar 120. Many of the smaller parties will not gain any seats in
the new parliament.
</P>
<P>
Forty-eight political parties took part in the election to
compete for 462 of the 500 seats in the House of Representatives
(DPR). The remaining 38 seats are reserved for the military, whose
members do not vote. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
