<HEADLINE> New System Gives Computer Users Alternative To U.S.'s Windows </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 3 (Xinhua) -- A new computer system called
Linux, which can provide a challenge to Microsoft's Windows system,
has just entered the Chinese market.
</P>
<P>
San Francisco's Turbolinux unveiled its simplified Chinese
version of the Turbolinux 4.0 at a press conference in China's
capital, China Securities reports.
</P>
<P>
The new software has been praised by computer enthusiasts
because its source code -- the programming language that makes it
run -- is freely available, allowing programmers to alter it to
suit their needs.
</P>
<P>
Like Windows, the system runs all applications on a computer
but unlike Windows, Linux can be downloaded for free off the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
Windows now runs nearly 90 percent of the world's personal
computers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
