<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Top NZ Foreign Policy Adviser favors Republic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The New Zealand Government's
top international policy adviser for the past eight years wants
New Zealand to become a republic and consider a common currency
with Australia.
</P>
<P>
Richard Nottage, who has just retired as secretary of Foreign
Affairs and Trade, was quoted by the New Zealand Press Association
(NZPA) Tuesday as saying that the prospect of New Zealand becoming
part of Australia does not daunt him. He also suggests a rethink
of some of New Zealand's free-market economic policies.
</P>
<P>
Nottage said the economic reforms of the past 15 years in the
country have not delivered the benefits that New Zealanders
"deserve" and he is "grieved" to see businesses shifting to
Australia and observe the drain of highly qualified New Zealanders
overseas.
</P>
<P>
"Although I would like New Zealand to have its own national
identity in some things, I myself under certain conditions would
be prepared to consider federation with Australia.
</P>
<P>
"It may be just the way the world is going, or regional blocs
are developing, that New Zealand and Australia are stuck down here
and have so much geographically in common. But first of all we'd
have to look at things like a common currency and it may be a long
way away," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I do believe New Zealand should become a republic. I've not
made any secret of that. I think the time has come," Nottage, with
a diplomatic career of 37 years, was quoted as saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
