<HEADLINE> Southern Chinese City Trying To Clean Up Air </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Guangzhou, the capital of south
China's Guangdong Province, will spend 70 million yuan on 11 new
trolley routes over the next five years, according to local
sources.
</P>
<P>
By then, the number of trolleys in service will be increased to
350. They are expected to help reduce air pollution caused by
exhaust gas and bringing back the city's green and its clear water
and blue skies.
</P>
<P>
The environmentally-friendly vehicles use electricity for power
and were available in Guangzhou by 1960, but have been little used
over the past three decades.
</P>
<P>
A new trolley service from Dongshan to the airport road opened
today, bringing the number of trolley routes in the city to eight.
There are 168 trolleys in operation in the city. 
</P>
</TEXT>
