<DOCNO> XIE19990803.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AIDS Prevalence Expected to Rise in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Prevalence of HIV infections is
expected to rise in Kenya in the coming years as there are no
signs of its decline, a report carried in the East African
Standard newspaper said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The report titled "AIDS in Kenya (1999)" issued by the
country's National AIDS/ STD Control Program said there had been
no evidence of a decline in prevalence and the trend of prevalence
suggests an increase to 15 percent from 14 percent in the 15-49
age group by 2005.
</P>
<P>
According to the National AIDS/STD Control Program, there are
areas in Kenya where prevalence already stands at 20-30 percent
as opposed to a gross projection of 18 percent in 1998 in high
dominance areas.
</P>
<P>
The report noted that AIDS prevention program implemented have
had an effect in reducing the severity of the epidemic but not to
the extent of preventing new inflections.
</P>
<P>
The population of adults living with HIV is larger in rural
areas, the report said, adding there are about 430,000
HIV-infected adults in urban areas in Kenya in addition to about
1.4 million in rural areas where some 80 percent of the country's
population live.
</P>
<P>
The report also noted that if the prevalence fails to hit the
expected 15 percent by 2005, the number of the infected would run
to 2.2 million by 2000 and three million by 2005.
</P>
<P>
"The cumulative number of AIDS would increase from over 700,000
deaths today to 2.7 million by 2005," the report added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
