<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Replaces Chief of State Arms Exporter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
has fired Lieutenant General Grigory Rapota from his post as head
of government arms trader Rosvooruzheniye, replacing him with
Kremlin staffer Alexei Ogaryov, the Itar-Tass news agency reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Rapota's ouster, predicted for weeks, was seen as another step
in the presidential entourage's drive to consolidate political and
economic control ahead of parliamentary and presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
Ogaryov, 42, had been described in news media as an ally of
Yeltsin's daughter and image adviser, Tatyana Dyachenko.
</P>
<P>
Rosvooruzheniye, which accounts for more than 80 percent of
Russia's arms exports, took commissions of 118 million U.S.
dollars on the 2.3 billion dollars worth of weaponry that the
company sold last year. It expects to sell 2.7 billion dollars of
arms this year, Rapota said last month. 
</P>
