<HEADLINE> Kenyan Official Calls for Legalizing Abortion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's new chief health civil
servant has called for legalizing abortion in a bid to secure
women's lives and health.
</P>
<P>
"There is no doubt the existing laws are colonial and too
strict in the modern society," said Julius Meme, the
newly-appointed permanent secretary in the ministry of health, the
Daily Nation newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He said legalizing abortion would save women from shying away
from help with doctors, citing that the current laws are to blame
for the rising number of abortion-related deaths.
</P>
<P>
Women used harmful drugs and needles or turned to crooked
quacks, Meme added.
</P>
<P>
He also called for a community-level discussion on the issue
with a view to eradicating the danger.
</P>
<P>
Meme, a former director of the Kenyatta National Hospital, also
demanded the introduction of sex education, arguing that it could
curb cases of school dropouts due to unwanted pregnancies and the
spread of HIV/AIDS.
</P>
<P>
Statistics by the United Nations Population Fund show that in
Kenya at least 50 percent of youths under 15 years old have had
sex. 
</P>
</TEXT>
