<DOCNO> XIE19990803.0226 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Officials Punished for Violating Environmental Regulations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, August 3 (Xinhua) -- A total of 22 government and
Chinese Communist Party officials in north China's Shanxi province
have been removed from their posts for breaching environmental
regulations.
</P>
<P>
The province penalized or punished the officials in accordance
with a set of newly-unveiled regulations concerning violations of
environmental regulations.
</P>
<P>
The regulations were worked out in face of increasing
violations of environmental regulations and loopholes in
penalizing the violators.
</P>
<P>
"In the past, only the units and individuals were held
responsible for violating environmental regulations, and there is
just no stipulations to restrict officials who have brought about
or harbored environment-damaging activities," said Yang Jichun,
director of the Provincial Environmental Protection Administration.
</P>
<P>
According to the regulations, government officials at all
levels will be held responsible for fulfilling environmental
protection goals, and those found of dereliction of duty,
harboring enterprises in violation of environmental regulations,
and deterring pollution reduction will receive administrative
penalties ranging from warning to removal from official posts.
</P>
<P>
The practice of penalizing responsible officials proved to be
effective in this regard and is expected to be adopted nationwide,
said an official from the State Environmental Protection
Administration.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
