<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northeast China Combats Tree Epidemic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The deadly tree epidemic,
poplar canker, has been put under basic control which had swept
across north and northeast China since May of this year.
</P>
<P>
Officials from the State Forestry Administration said that
further infestation would be effectively prevented. Trees found
seriously attacked have been felled while chemical pesticides were
applied on those diseased trees for treatment.
</P>
<P>
The epidemic was caused by bacteria-carrying parasites in the
trees. The bacteria has destroyed approximately 30,000 trees -
causing withering and rotting of their bark - in Shenyang City,
capital of Liaoning Province, Harbin City, capital of Heilongjiang
Province and Tianjin Municipality.
</P>
<P>
The disease has been detected in Changchun, Dalian, Anshan and
Qinhuangdao in Jilin, Liaoning and Hebei provinces, statistics
from the State Forestry Administration showed.
</P>
<P>
The epidemic's outbreak was "unprecedented and unexpected," and
was a result of abnormal weather conditions since last winter,
administration officials suggested.
</P>
<P>
"Last winter's drought reduced the water in the trees, which
weakened their ability to fight bacteria," noted Wang Xiaohua,
division director of the administration's Anti-Pest and Disease
Center.
</P>
<P>
"Another reason is the spring's humidity was good for the
growth of the bacteria," Wang added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
