<HEADLINE> Journalists Appointed to Be Judicial Supervisors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The Xicheng District Court in
this Chinese Capital has appointed a group of journalists to be
court supervisors to supervise its judicial work.
</P>
<P>
As the first group of journalists to act as judicial
supervisors in Beijing, the reporters will watch court activities
and see whether the court officials are abiding by judicial ethics
and being self-disciplined in law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
"We introduce the reporter supervisors as one of the steps to
increase judicial transparency and ensure judicial justice," said
Guo Shenggui, president of the district court.
</P>
<P>
Located in central part of Beijing, Xicheng district is known
for increasing occurrence of complex crimes, which have been
rising at an average rate of 15 percent annually.
</P>
<P>
The district court handled a total of over 5,400 cases during
the first half of this year, a rise of 23.6 percent over the same
period last year. Of the total, more than 5,000 cases were
concluded during the period, up 31.3 percent from last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
