<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Belgium to Investigate Stowaway Flight Death </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 3 (Xinhua) -- An autopsy is scheduled for
Tuesday by Belgian justice authorities to examine the cause of the
death of two African youths who were found in a compartment for
storing landing gears under the wing of a Sabena airliner.
</P>
<P>
The two African youths, judged to be in their mid teens, were
found dead inside the right under-the-wing compartment at the
airport of the Belgian national airport on Monday.
</P>
<P>
A strange odor led airport re-fueling technicians to the
discovery of the bodies from the compartment of the Airbus A330-
300.
</P>
<P>
The airport medical personnel said that the deaths could be
caused by the low temperature high up in the sky during the flight.
</P>
<P>
The Sabena airliner initiated its flight from Bamako of Mali
with a stopover at Conakry of Guinea before arriving in the
Belgian capital.
</P>
<P>
No one knows for sure where the two stowaways got into the
compartment though the compartment is supposed to be routinely
checked at each airport before taking off.
</P>
<P>
The Sabena authorities decided to take proper measures to
prevent similar events from happening again in the future. But
they have to decide what measures to take in the first place. Some
suggested tighter checks before taking off.
</P>
<P>
At the cruise height of 10,000 meters, the ambient temperature
around the airplane can be 50 degrees or 55 degrees Celsius below
zero. Though it may be a bit warmer inside the landing gear
compartment, the lack of oxygen at that altitude is another deadly
factor during flight.
</P>
<P>
The chance is rare for anyone to survive such a stowaway voyage
though a Senegalese youth managed to survive a five-hour stowaway
flight from Dakar to Lyon of France on January 26 this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990803.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
