<HEADLINE> Indian Railway Minister to Quit for Major Accident </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Indian Railway Minister Nitish
Kumar Tuesday announced his decision to resign to take moral
responsibility for Monday's train disaster in West Bengal, which
claimed over 300 lives.
</P>
<P>
He told a press conference in Patna, West Bengal, that he had
already apprised Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee of his
decision and would leave for Delhi later in the day to hand over
the resignation letter.
</P>
<P>
Kumar, who also holds the additional charge of the surface
transport ministry, said he would resign from the council of
ministers.
</P>
<P>
He admitted that human error prima facie appeared to be the
cause of the accident and held the failure of the railway system
responsible for the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
Some 220 bodies had already been extricated from the wreckage
of the two colliding trains, he added. 
</P>
