<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Snow Leopard: Mascot of the 8th SAF Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The Snow Leopard wearing a
traditional Nepali Topi (Cap), is the official Mascot of the 8th
SAF Games, said a press release here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Snow Leopard, which is listed among protected animals of
the Nepali government since 1973, can be found in the high
Himalaya, west of the Qomolangma region at an altitude between
3000m to 4000m, and comes down to lower elevation (2000m) during
the winter season.
</P>
<P>
The animal, which is similar to common leopard, favours dry
Alpine Steppe habitat. Its head is squarish, with a high forehead
and vertical thin and measures from 190 to 200 centimeters in
total length.
</P>
<P>
Since the last century its population has greatly dwindled as
its beautiful and soft skin make costly dresses and luxury items.
To conserve these beautiful animals, a ban on the trade of its fur
has also been imposed by the International Fur Trade Federation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990803.0243 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Approves Release of Crucial Aid to Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary Fund
(IMF) has finally approved the 193 million U.S. dollars stand-by
credit facility for Zimbabwe, ending almost two years of an
agonizing wait for its disbursement.
</P>
<P>
At its meeting in Washington Monday, the IMF board finally
approved the release of the crucial aid which will support the
country's economic reform program over the next 14 months, the
daily Herald newspaper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Of this amount, 24 million U.S. dollars will be available
immediately while another 9.7 million U.S. dollars will be
released after August 16. Subsequent disbursements will depend on
the country's performance in meeting the agreed targets.
</P>
<P>
In coming to its decision, the IMF had noted several key areas
which it said needed to be resolved. Inflationary pressures will
have to be monitored while the Zimbabwean government will have to
restrain its expenditure.
</P>
<P>
The IMF said in a statement last night that the stabilization
of the country's economy will center on, among other things,
monetary growth control.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe would also have to implement the land reform program
in a transparent manner, with all stake-holders consulted.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe's participation in the Democratic Republic of Congo
also came under the spotlight. Although not mentioned by name,
the IMF wants the Zimbabwean government to make public its
military expenditure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990803.0244 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
