<HEADLINE> Ugandan Minister Blamed for Sale of Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan Finance Minister Gerald
Ssendaula has been blamed by members of parliament (MPs) for
selling the Cooperative Bank which was closed in May for
insolvency.
</P>
<P>
MPs expressed overwhelming support for a motion asking the
minister to cancel the sale of the bank until a select committee
on the financial sector crises reports to the House, the New
Vision paper reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
They also called on Governor of the Bank of Uganda Charles
Kikonyogo to resign if he could not resist the political pressure
in the supervision of financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
Ssendaula defended the central bank's decision to close and
sell the Cooperative Bank branches, saying the bank was insolvent
and mismanaged.
</P>
<P>
The bank, which had about 110,000 depositors, was abruptly
closed, leaving many of the its depositors crying out for their
money.
</P>
<P>
Some reports here said that the central bank sold the branches
of the closed bank subsequently while others indicated that the
bank was sold in January, four months before its closure. 
</P>
