<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Half of India's Rural Population Illiterate: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Half of the population in rural
India are illiterate with about 40 percent living below the
poverty line, according to a latest study by India's National
Council of Applied Economic Research (NCAER).
</P>
<P>
Only 43 percent of rural households have access to domestic
lighting, 23 percent have access to tap water and 33 percent
utilize the public distribution system, the NCAER said in its
study.
</P>
<P>
The report, which was released on Monday, showed that on
average, 8 percent of rural income was spend on health and primary
education.
</P>
<P>
The report was based on a sample survey conducted in 1994
covering 33,000 rural households from 1,765 villages and 195
districts in 15 states and the northeast.
</P>
<P>
It has taken into account 90 indicators of human development
representing various dimensions of living standards, including
income and assets, employment and wages, consumption, literacy and
health.
</P>
<P>
The report identifies the rural people as farmers, wage
laborers, scheduled castes and scheduled tribes and those living
in less developed villages.
</P>
<P>
It also presents a number of human development parameters
according to religion and caste.
</P>
<P>
About 16 percent of the people investigated belong to the
lowest strata in India's traditional caste system and have an
income of only 3 rupees (7 U.S. cents) one person per day, and the
next 18 percent have command over only 5.50 rupees (13 U.S. cents)
per person per day, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
