<DOCNO> XIE19990803.0248 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Calls for Concerted Efforts in Fighting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Gold-producing developing
countries should unite to fight the proposed International
Monetary Fund (IMF) gold sales and even seek the intervention of
the United Nations on the issue, a Zimbabwean minister has said.
</P>
<P>
Simon Moyo, Minister of Mines, Environment and Tourism, told
the daily Herald that the proposed gold sales posed a major threat
to gold-producing countries, particularly developing ones.
</P>
<P>
The IMF intends to sell 10 million ounces of its gold and use
the proceeds to help highly indebted developing countries reduce
their debt.
</P>
<P>
But critics say while the objective to help poor countries
offset their debts is welcome, the gold sales would plunge poor
countries into deeper economic problems since many of them
depended on gold. If approved, the IMF proposal would result in
gold prices, which are already low, tumbling further and resulting
in massive retrenchments in the gold mining sector.
</P>
<P>
In Zimbabwe, it is feared that 30,000 jobs would be lost if the
IMF off loads its gold. 
</P>
</TEXT>
