<DOCNO> XIE19990803.0252 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SES, SIMEX Moving Toward Integration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Work on the merger of
Singapore's equities and futures exchanges has witnessed progress
and the search for top executives of the new integrated exchange
has been underway, according to local press reports.
</P>
<P>
The merger process of combining the Stock Exchange of Singapore
(SES) and the Singapore International Monetary Exchange (SIMEX)
has reached the stage where the new legal and organization
structure has been approved by the pro tem committee appointed by
the Monetary Authority of Singapore (MAS).
</P>
<P>
The SES-SIMEX merger was announced by the Singapore Government
last year as part of financial reform with a view to strengthening
its financial sector.
</P>
<P>
The new exchange will be set up as a holding company with five
wholly-owned subsidiaries and will be led jointly by a chief
executive officer (CEO) and presidents in the Office of the Chief
Executive.
</P>
<P>
By the organizational echelon of the new exchange, the CEO will
oversee nine divisions, including the four business units of cash
trading, derivatives trading, cash clearing and derivatives
clearing, and five functional departments in charge of strategy,
information technology, risk management and regulatory functions.
</P>
<P>
The four business units will be kept separate to focus on their
individual profit-and-loss generation.
</P>
<P>
The reports said the new organization structure is designed to
make the exchange more commercial-minded as it will eventually be
publicly listed.
</P>
<P>
The work of looking for top executives and board members of the
new exchange is still underway but the heads of six divisions have
been appointed and the heads of the other three divisions will be
recruited from the outside.
</P>
<P>
The reports said one crucial task left is the common bond
system of SIMEX's clearing house which has to be modified or
replaced because it is incompatible with demutualization and
merger.
</P>
<P>
SES and SIMEX have recently assured their members in a letter
that "under no circumstances will the financial strength and the
integrity of the SIMEX clearing house be allowed to weaken."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
