<HEADLINE> Deutsche Bank Optimistic About Euro Zone Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FRANKFURT, August 2 (Xinhua) -- The economy in the euro zone in
2000 will rise to 3 percent from this year's projected 2 percent,
Deutsche Bank AG analysts predicted here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
They said industrial exports and private consumption will be
the main pillars for the development in the euro zone.
</P>
<P>
The zone will benefit greatly from the robust world economy and
the euro slip in the past few months, they added.
</P>
<P>
The German economy in 2000 will rise to 3 percent from this
year's predicted 1.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
Deutsche Bank AG, one of the world's largest, said German
exports are expected to reach 6.7 percent of the country's total
economy next year. From the latter half of this year, private
consumption, especially auto and tourism spending, will maintain
growing momentum, thus boosting the German economy.
</P>
<P>
From 2001, the growing momentum of the euro zone economy will
be better than that of the U.S. economy, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
It said by the end of 2000 the exchange rate of the euro will
rise to 1.15 to 1.20 U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
