<HEADLINE> Xie, Galliamova Tie at World Chess Championship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAZAN, Russia, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Xie Jun of China and
Russian Alisa Galliamova were deadlocked in a close showdown as
they fought to the second tie after the fourth round of the world
women's chess championship here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
They both failed to find the weak points of each other and
agreed to draw at the 34th move, the second after they fought to a
tie at the opening game on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Up to now the two elite players, who also beat each other once
in the last two rounds, collected two points from the same 1-2-1
record.
</P>
<P>
The championship, which is shared by China and Russia, will
have its first eight rounds from July 29 to August 9 here and the
next eight rounds from August 13 to 25 at Shenyang, northeast
China.
</P>
<P>
As is regulated by the FIDE, the chess world governing body,
either player who first collected 8.5 points will be the winner
and a play-off is needed if both sides tie 8-all. 
</P>
