Joanne Malar blazed her way to women's 400m individual medley
in a Games record-breaking time of four minutes 38.46 seconds,
ripping more than five seconds off the previous best mark of 4:43.
64, set by herself four years ago in Argentina.
</P>
<P>
Malar went on to inspire her Canadian teammates Jessica Deglau,
M.L. Timpert and Laura Nicholls to another successful assault on
the Games record, timing eight minutes 5.56 seconds to win women's
4X200 freestyle relay title.
</P>
<P>
The old mark had been 8:07.30, set by the United States in the
1995 Games.
</P>
<P>
In the women's 100m freestyle, Nichollis sported golden again
by touching in 56.25, with American Tammie Spatz finishing second
closely in 56.44.
</P>
<P>
Ed Moses squeezed down his own best time of 1:01.06, which came
from this morning's prelims, to 1:00.99 to take the gold in the
men's 100m breastroke.
</P>
<P>
Brazil's Gustavo Borges clocked 1:49.41 to clinch the men's
200m freestyle title.
</P>
<P>
Elsewhere today, Bermuda scored its first gold since the
beginning of the Games as M.J. Tumbridege garnered 74 points to
triumph in the equestrian competitions.
</P>
<P>
In the men's volleyball final, Cuba toughed out a 25-20, 14-25,
17-25, 25-23, 15-12 victory over Brazil for the gold medal.
</P>
<P>
The United States continued their unshakable lead in the medals
count with 74 golds, followed by Cuba, who swept away four Judo
golds today to boost their tally to 37, and Canada, whose golds
registered 33. 
</P>
</TEXT>
