<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flash Floods Hit Central Philippines, Killing 19 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 3 (Xinhua) -- Flash floods caused by two days of
torrential rains starting Sunday have hit Metro Manila and nearby
provinces with 19 people killed and more than 3,000 families
evacuated from their homes.
</P>
<P>
According to the National Disaster Coordination Council, seven
people from two families were killed in Antipolo when a concrete
wall of a low-cost housing project fell on their houses early
Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
Flash floods also caused landslides in the Cainta area of
Manila Sunday night, killing seven people of one family.
</P>
<P>
In Metro Manila, the top disaster area in the nation, 178
villages have been submerged, forcing the evacuation of residents
in low-lying areas, Metropolitan Manila Development Authority
said.
</P>
<P>
Due to the widespread flooding and hard weather in Metro
Manila, the Philippine government has suspended work in all
government offices effective 3:00 p.m. Monday.
</P>
<P>
In the nearby Pampanga province, continuous rains destroyed a
40-meter dike of the Pampanga river and inundated 11 towns as of
Monday noon.
</P>
<P>
Floods and erosion in the province rendered some portions of
national and provincial roads impassable to all types of vehicles
and forced at least 100 people to evacuate to safer places.
</P>
<P>
In Manila and Rizal, classes were suspended in all public and
private schools due to flash floods spawned by two days of
torrential rains.
</P>
<P>
Philippine President Joseph Estrada said Monday that he had
instructed the armed forces and police to be on red alert to
enable them to undertake round-the-clock rescue and relief
operations in disaster areas.
</P>
<P>
Defense Secretary Orlando Mercado said mayors and governors of
affected communities can, on their own, declare a state of
calamity in a bid to authorize the release of disaster-relief
funds.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Mercado said the military has sent out trucks and
rubber boats to assist families affected by the floods.
</P>
<P>
Torrential rains, reportedly induced by the much-feared La Nina
phenomenon, would continue to pelt Manila and nearby provinces
Tuesday, weather reports said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
