<HEADLINE> OPEC Oil Price Further Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, August 2 (Xinhua) -- The average crude oil price
continued rising this week to a two-year high of 18.90 U.S.
dollars per barrel, 40 cents more than that of last week,
according to figures released by the secretariat of the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The price has been increasing since June, when it was 15.61
dollars per barrel. In July, it reached 18.31 dollars, said the
report.
</P>
<P>
Analysts attributed the price hike to OPEC members sticking to
the agreement reached in March of reducing oil production to
protect the price.
</P>
<P>
Higher international demand and lower consumer storage are also
factors pushing the price up, they said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
