<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Argentine Industrialists Call for Economic Coordination with Mercosur </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES, August 2 (Xinhua)-- Argentine industrialists
Monday called for the negotiation of a mechanism to coordinate the
macro-economic behavior of the Southern Common Market (Mercosur).
</P>
<P>
During a lunch attended by the country's main entrepreneurs and
Minister of Economy Roque Fernandez, the head of Argentina's
Industrial Union Osvaldo Rial said coordinating macroeconomics
among the four countries was a matter of extreme urgency, a matter
of such high priority that Mercosur should devote full attention
to its accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
He said a mechanism is needed so that when a macro-economic
variation occurs in any one of the countries, such as in the case
of Brazil's devaluation of its currency, the others can take
transitory compensating measures until the situation is re-
established.
</P>
<P>
He said the industrialists would meet Tuesday with officials
from the Ministry of Economy and Foreign Affairs in order to
coordinate the position before Mercosur's next meeting in
Montevideo.
</P>
<P>
He denounced the devaluation of Brazil's currency, the real,
which caused considerable losses to Argentina's industrial sector.
He added that a means of finding compensation must be found.
</P>
<P>
Argentine President Carlos Menem promised his Brazilian
counterpart Enrique Cardoso that Argentina won't take
protectionist measures against Brazil's exports in the areas of
textiles, shoes, electronic products, and other areas in order to
preserve Mercosur's integration.
</P>
<P>
Local industrialists however protested against the government's
position, accusing it of not protecting national industries.
</P>
<P>
The largest regional group in South America, Mercosur, which
includes Argentina, Brazil, Uruguay and Paraguay, is facing its
worst crisis since it went into effect in 1995. Bolivia and Chile
are associate members. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
