<HEADLINE> China Steps Up Efforts to Reform SOEs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 3 (Xinhua) -- China today announced some new
policies to help State-owned enterprises (SOEs) shake off
difficulties in three years (1998-2000).
</P>
<P>
Zheng Silin, vice-minister of the State Economic and Trade
Commission, told a news conference here today that the following
seven important measures must be fully implemented in the second
half of the year in order to realize the objectives of the three-
year reform set for the SOEs:
</P>
<P>
-- Controlling the total quantity and phasing out the backward
production equipment;
</P>
<P>
-- Intensifying efforts to develop market and regulating market
order;
</P>
<P>
-- Quickening the pace of mergers and bankruptcy and promoting
SOEs' restructuring and reorganization;
</P>
<P>
-- Doing a good job of transferring creditor's rights into
stockholder's rights;
</P>
<P>
-- Supporting major technical renovations and stepping up
industrial upgrading;
</P>
<P>
-- Increasing fund-raising channels and promoting social
security systems; and
</P>
<P>
-- Cleaning up arrears and speeding up the fund turnover of
enterprises. 
</P>
