<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Remains Polio-free </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 3 (Xinhua) -- The Ministry of Health intends to
carry out a supplementary vaccination campaign later this year to
ensure the country remains polio-free, today's "China Daily"
reported.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing-based English newspaper quoted Zhou Jun, an
official from the ministry as saying that the vaccination campaign
will target some 30 million children under fours of age of
transient workers and in border and flood-stricken areas.
</P>
<P>
China's action is part of a global campaign to eradicate polio
by next year. Several United Nations agencies, the Japanese
International Co-operation Agency and the U.S. Center for Disease
Control and Prevention will provide funding.
</P>
<P>
The World Health Organization (WHO) vowed to wipe out vaccine-
preventable polio in all countries by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The ministry started a national program for polio eradication
in 1988 and achieved an immunization rate of 85 percent at
provincial level the same year.
</P>
<P>
The last native "wild" polio case was reported in September
1994. Since then, only four imported cases have been reported in
1995-96 in Yunnan Province, affecting people returning from
Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
China still faces a polio threat from neighboring areas and it
is difficult to have all children with transient families
vaccinated.
</P>
<P>
China, like other countries in the WHO Western Pacific Region,
will report on the development of its polio eradication action to
the WHO regional office this week. A final report will be
submitted to WHO for certification next year, according to the
paper. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990803.0283 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
