<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lower Inflation Predicted for 1999 in Mexico </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, August 2 (Xinhua)-- Mexican Finance Secretary Jose
Angel Gurria said Monday that inflation will reach 13 percent in
1999, a lower figure than in 1998, due to an improvement in the
economy.
</P>
<P>
Inflation is maintaining a downward trend as is unemployment in
Mexico, Gurria said during the 17th meeting of the Latin American
Econometric Society in Cancun, east of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
Mexico registered an inflation rate of 18.6 percent last year,
above the 15.7 percent rate of 1997, as a result of the financial
crisis and the fall of oil prices on the world market.
</P>
<P>
The Mexican government launched financial reforms to increase
tax revenues, reduce dependency on petroleum income, and support
the productive sectors.
</P>
<P>
Without providing figures, Gurria said that unemployment stayed
in the first quarter of this year at its lowest level since 1991.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
