<HEADLINE> Colombian President Urges Guerrillas to Free Hostages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Colombian President
Andres Pastrana urged on Monday the Army of National Liberation (
ELN), the country's second largest guerrilla group, to release
civilian hostages.
</P>
<P>
Pastana's demand echoed a request included in a letter sent to
the government and the ELN respectively by a group of
personalities from all walks of life including Gabriel Garcia
Marquez, a winner of the Nobel Prize of Literature.
</P>
<P>
The president also renewed his call for peace talks with the
ELN on the basis of just and the immediate and unconditional free
of the hostages.
</P>
<P>
Pastrana said the government is ready to evaluate the ELN offer
to establish a demilitarized zone in the north of the country.
</P>
<P>
The ELN is holding 70 civilians as hostages, 45 of which were
kidnapped on May 30 from a church and 16 from a commercial
airliner the guerrilla hijacked on April 12.
</P>
<P>
The talks between the Pastana's government and the
Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia (FARC), the country's
largest guerrilla group, on the establishment of a large
demilitarized zone in southern Colombia, collapsed on July 17.
</P>
<P>
The 35-year civil war in Colombia has killed some 120,000
people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
