<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Construction Spending Rebounds Slightly in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 2 (Xinhua) -- The Commerce Department said
Monday that U.S. construction spending rebounded slightly in June,
rising 0.5 percent to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 699.4
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
June's increase followed the drops of 1.4 percent in both May
and April, the Department said.
</P>
<P>
The increases in June were widespread with gains reported in
office buildings, industrial buildings, hotels and big government
projects. But spending on all residential construction dropped 0.3
percent.
</P>
<P>
The Department's report showed that spending on all private
construction projects jumped 0.6 percent in June to a seasonally
adjusted annual rate of 550 billion dollars. The private
construction spending, after having declines in May and April, was
the main factor in the overall gain in June's construction
spending.
</P>
<P>
Spending on government construction projects also rebounded in
June, rising 0.2 percent to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of
149.4 billion dollars, after having fallen three straight months
in a row.
</P>
<P>
Spending on all residential projects, however, fell 0.3 percent
in June to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 322 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
In a separate report, the National Association of Purchasing
said Monday that the U.S. manufacturing sector grew in July for
the sixth consecutive month.
</P>
<P>
The Association said its monthly index of manufacturing
activity registered 53.4 percent in July, compared to 57 percent
in June. Figures above 50 percent indicate growth.
</P>
<P>
The purchasing managers group, which represents executives
who buy raw materials and supplies for industry, also reported a
slightly stronger rise in July raw-material prices than in June.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
