<HEADLINE> American Moses Breaks Pan Am Record at Swimming Heats </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WINNIPEG, Canada, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Ed Moses plunged into
the Pan Am pool with a splash as the American broke the meet
record in the men's 100m breaststroke preliminaries on the first
day of the swimming competitions.
</P>
<P>
His time of 1:01.06 makes him the fifth-fasted man ever and the
second-fastest American, behind Jeremy Linn's 1:00.77.
</P>
<P>
"I want to swim a smooth race and finish strong so I would have
confidence for tonight," Moses said. "I was hoping to break a 1:02,
just hoping for a best time. I was excited (when I saw the time).
</P>
<P>
"I have plenty left to give tonight. Morgan Knabe (Canada) has
been swimming well all year and Jarrod (Marrs) qualified right
behind him. So it should be exciting tonight."
</P>
<P>
Moses wasn't the only highlight for the United States in this
morning's prelims as every single American competitor advance to
finals.
</P>
<P>
Tammie Spatz and Jen Eberwein are the top two seeds in the 100m
freestyle, after posting times of 56.49 and 57.05.
</P>
<P>
Jarrod Marrs qualified third in the 100m breastroke with a 1:02.
61, joining Moses in the final.
</P>
<P>
Canada's Joanne Malar chalked up the fastest time of 4:44.34 in
the 400m individual medley.
</P>
<P>
Gustavo Borges of Brazil came atop in the men's 200m freestyle
with a time of 1:50.99, followed by American Scott Tucker, whose
time registered 1:51.71. 
</P>
</TEXT>
