<DOCNO> XIE19990803.0298 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FA Probe Ferguson 'Bung' Revelation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 2 (Xinhua) -- The Football Association of
England are to contact Manchester United football club manager Sir
Alex Ferguson over his revelations that he was offered a 40,000
pounds bung.
</P>
<P>
The FA are not questioning the Manchester United manager's
conduct in the affair and they believe he did everything above
board. They want to know the full facts before they pass on their
report to FIFA and the FA's compliance officer, Graham Bean, will
be contacting Sir Alex.
</P>
<P>
Sir Alex reveals in his autobiography, Managing My Life, that
he was handed the money in a parcel by Grigory Essaoulenko, the
Russian agent who attempted to force through the transfer of
Russian forward Andrei Kanchelskis from United to Everton, in 1994.
He notified United straight away and the money lay in the club
safe for nearly a year before he handed it back to Essaoulenko.
</P>
<P>
FA spokesman Adrian Bevington said: "This is a matter for FIFA.
However, our compliance officer, Graham Bean, will be contacting
Sir Alex Ferguson to request the full facts surrounding this issue.
</P>
<P>
"Once the facts have been established, we will pass on all the
information to FIFA. They will probably wish to carry out an
investigation into this agent."
</P>
<P>
FIFA are waiting for the FA's report before making any official
comment.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman said: "At the moment everything is happening in the
media and we do not wish to make any official statement until we
receive further information from the FA."
</P>
<P>
The matter is complicated by the fact that FIFA only began to
license agents a year after Essaoulenko offered the money to Sir
Alex. The FIFA spokesman also confirmed that Essaoulenko is not on
their list of licensed agents.
</P>
<P>
The Premier League bungs inquiry investigated the transfer of
Kanchelskis, who later moved to Everton on five million pounds,
and spokesman Mike Lee claims there is no need for them to re-open
their inquiries.
</P>
<P>
"The Kanchelskis transfer was looked into and there's
absolutely no question of any wrong-doing by anyone involved at
Manchester United or English football," he said. "There is nothing
further to investigate." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
