<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0030 GMT, August 3 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA -- The North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) will
send new troops by September to replace its forces currently
stationed in Albania called the AFOR, or the majority of them, an
AFOR press officer here said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Most of the AFOR are expected to leave Albania on September 1
as their "humanitarian mission" is closing, said Lt. Col. Helge
Eriksen. The details of the mission of new NATO forces and its
commander have not been clearly decided by the North Atlantic
Council so far, but the council has decided that NATO will remain
in Albania, he said. (Albania-NATO-Forces)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- A top Russian defense official said Monday that an
early warning facility in Branovichi of western Belarus will be
tested before the end of the year and "supplied to the armed
forces in 2000."
</P>
<P>
The early warning facility is expected to restore the single
radar field over the western and northwestern sectors after the
elimination of the radar facilities in Skrunde, Latvia, said
Colonel-General Vladimir Yakovlev, commander of the Russian
Strategic Rocket Forces, during a trip to Baranovichi. "The radar
facilities at Skrunde will be completely decommissioned this year,
" the Interfax quoted Yakovlev as saying. (Russia-Defense-Early
Warning System)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Two Palestinian groups on Monday underlined the need
for joint efforts to reach a national reconciliation for
recovering the legitimate rights of the Palestinian people.
</P>
<P>
The Fatah movement, led by Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat,
and the radical Damascus-based Popular Front for the Liberation of
Palestine (PFLP) held talks on Sunday in Cairo on ways of healing
rifts and mending fences. A joint communique was issued on Monday
on the talks. In the communique, the two groups emphasized the
necessity to hold dialog among all Palestinian forces to augment
national reconciliation and unity. (Egypt-Palestinians-Communique)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States would continue its agreement
with the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) on building
a 5 billion U.S. dollars nuclear power even if Pyongyang conducts
a long-range missile test, the State Department said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
"We think that regardless of what serious consequences there
might be for the potential for the U.S.- North Korean development,
if the North Koreans test, we shouldn't cut off our nose to spite
our face," State Department spokesman James Rubin told reporters.
"The agreed framework is a very important instrument that benefits
the security of the United States and the countries in the region,
" he added.(US-DPRK-Framework) 
</P>
</TEXT>
