<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Disgraced Canadian Goalie Appologizes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WINNIPEG, Canada, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Steve Vezina, whose
steroid-laced urine cost the Canadian roller-hockey team gold at
the Pan American Games, appologized to the whole country at a news
conference on Monday.
</P>
<P>
"The whole thing affected me very much. I am regretful about it,
" Vezina said.
</P>
<P>
He went on to appologize to the entire country of Canada, his
teammates and everyone associated with the 13th Pan Am Games.
</P>
<P>
"But I don't think I'm a bad athlete, or a bad goalie. I'm not
the only one who takes these things.
</P>
<P>
"I didn't commit any crime. It's a misunderstanding. I've taken
something I shouldn't have taken."
</P>
<P>
Canada was stripped of its roller hockey gold medal yesterday
after Vezina tested positive for two stimulants and an anabolic
steroid.
</P>
<P>
Vezina was the lone Canadian roller hockey player tested
positive. Eduardo de Rose, the chief of the Games Medical
Commission, said Vezina's sample showed an excessively high level
of the steroid Nandrolone--16,000 parts per million compared to
the acceptable level of two parts per million.
</P>
<P>
Vezina, 24, plays a professional roller hockey for the Buffalo
Wings.
</P>
<P>
He said his professional schedule is very demanding and the
drug "helps me a lot"."It helps me to be physically strong and
recover fast."
</P>
<P>
The drug test showed three banned substances--ephedrine, pseudo-
ephedrine and Nandrolone. The former two are stimulants used to
avoid fatigue and Nandrolone is an anabolic steroid that increases
muscle mass.
</P>
<P>
Ephedrine and Nandrolone are not taken for the Pan Am Games,
Vezina said, They're taken as soon as in June for his professional
training.
</P>
<P>
But he said the incident is not going to change his attitude.
</P>
<P>
"I'll be careful. I've learned a lesson." he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
