<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Says to Continue Framework Agreement with DPRK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 2 (Xinhua) -- The United States would
continue its agreement with the Democratic People's Republic of
Korea (DPRK) on building a 5 billion U.S. dollars nuclear power
even if Pyongyang conducts a long-range missile test, the State
Department said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
"We think that regardless of what serious consequences there
might be for the potential for the U.S.- North Korean
development, if the North Koreans test, we shouldn't cut off our
nose to spite our face," State Department spokesman James Rubin
told reporters.
</P>
<P>
"The agreed framework is a very important instrument that
benefits the security of the United States and the countries in
the region," he said
</P>
<P>
"And we would intend and want to see that program and
agreement continued, even if we have problems and serious
concerns about the missiles," he added.
</P>
<P>
Under the 1994 agreed framework, the United States committed
to providing two light-water nuclear power reactors and
alternative energy supplies in exchange for DPRK's stopping
using of the graphite reactors.
</P>
<P>
As a part of the project, the United States has promised to pay
20 million dollars to 30 dolalrs million annually for oil
shipments to the DPRK. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990803.0310 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Approves 193 Million Dollars in Credit for Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 2 (Xinhua) -- The International Monetary
Fund (IMF) on Monday approved a stand-by credit of 193 million
U.S. dollars for Zimbabwe, which is designed to support the
nation's economic program over the next 14 months.
</P>
<P>
Of the total, 24 million dollars is available for Zimbabwe
immediately.
</P>
<P>
"Directors...underscored that the immediate challenge is to
stabilize the exchange rate and bring inflation under control
through a further tightening of financial policies," IMF Deputy
Managing Director Shigemitsu Sugisaki said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"The government's economic program for 1999 seeks to dampen
inflationary pressures, restore a visible external position and
provide a springboard for economic growth," the IMF said.
</P>
<P>
"The stabilization effort centers on continued financial
restraint, including recent steps to bring monetary growth under
control," it added.
</P>
<P>
Projected growth in real gross domestic product is 1.2 percent
in 1999, which reflects a significant downward revision from
previous expectations because of lower output in the mining and
manufacturing sectors, the IMF said.
</P>
<P>
The government's inflation target for end-1999 is 30 percent,
which is to be achieved by containing money supply growth. The
inflation rate was 46.6 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The IMF said Zimbabwe would receive an additional 9.7 million
dollars on August 16. Further payments would be made available
quarterly if Zimbabwe met its promises on economic reform.
</P>
<P>
The IMF withheld payments from previous credits to Zimbabwe
because of concern about prices, land reforms and the budget.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
