<HEADLINE> New UNDP Administrator Makes First Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 2 (Xinhua) -- The administrator of the
United Nations Development Program (UNDP), Mark Brown, is visiting
Japan and China this week to forge new strategic partnerships in
both countries, a UNDP news release said Monday.
</P>
<P>
"This is his first trip to Asia since assuming office on July
1," said the news release.
</P>
<P>
Brown is scheduled to meet a range of top ranking government
officials and representatives of academia, civil society and
private sectors in the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Brown Monday met with Kazuo Aichi, the chairman of Japan's
Special Committee on External Economic Relations on the Liberal
Democratic Party and Member of the House of Representatives of the
Diet, or Parliament. He is also expected to discuss with Japanese
Foreign Minister Masahiko Kohmura.
</P>
<P>
Brown will travel to China on August 5 for a two-day visit for
talks with Chinese leaders on the work of UNDP in China and the
role of China in the global development agenda.
</P>
<P>
China is one of UNDP's largest program countries, and the
only one that has a permanent seat on the U.N. Security Council,
said the UNDP news release.
</P>
<P>
UNDP has played a key role in China's reform agenda, and
celebrates 20 years of partnership with China this September,
the news release added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
