<DOCNO> XIE19990803.0313 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks Finish Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
NEW YORK, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Wall Street stocks finished
lower Monday in a mixed bag of economic signals.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average closed down 9.19 at
10,645.96. The Blue chip index fell 255.81 points or 2.31
percent last week.
</P>
<P>
The market rallied as investors eased fears about higher
interests after the National Association of Purchasing Management
reported that the U.S. manufacturing sector grew in July for the
sixth consecutive month, but not as strongly as most analysts
expected. The Dow rose as much as 136 points earlier in the
session.
</P>
<P>
But a separate report by the Commerce Department said
construction spending rose 0.5 percent in June after fallings
in two straight months. The report reminded investors of
possibility of higher interest rates and the market retreated
from the early gains, moving into negative territory.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators were also lower. The Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index fell 0.67 to 1,328.05 and the technology heavy
Nasdaq composite index fell 14.86 at 2,623.63.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE composite index fell 0.73 at 625.34 and the
American Stock Exchange index fell 4.59 at 783.64. The Russell
2000 index of smaller companies fell 2.14 at 442.63.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 7-to-5 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with 1,762 down, 1,225 up and 541
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume declined to 721.29 million shares from 761.98
million in the previous session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
